name: Banning Genesis
description: A great warm up or first outside bolder for beginners. Stand start on the ground and use the detached rock at the bottom to climb straight up the line where the rock color changes. Top out is probably the crux but not out of line for the rest of the climb. Landing is pretty flat but there is a detached rock/boulder at the bottom that could come into play but probably wont. A couple pads are a good idea.

name: Booster Shot
description: Sit start with both hands on a wide ledge about 2 feet off the ground. Feet can go anywhere on or underneath the boulder, as long as they aren't on the dirt. Only use the holds that are directly above the starting ledge. Top out under the right side of the roof, then exit to the right of the roof.     Downclimb it or walk uphill to get back to a trail. Once on the trail, take a left to get back to the Teacher's Overlook.

name: Clouds
description: This route climbs better than it looks. Sit start low on the left side of the cave-ish area, Climb out left and top out straight up. The somewhat detached blocks above are on, but the detached blocks at the base of the vertical face and the completely separate boulder to the right are off.

name: The Coach
description: Big moves from the ledge to the sleepy slot.

name: Creeper
description: Sit start the same start as Clouds. Veer right under the overhang and onto the face. Top out without using the huge detached block on top.

name: Cutting Class
description: Start in the slot on a ledge. Small crimps and perm-moist holds gain the lip.

name: The Easiest Route in Thailand
description: Sit or squat start from the same spot as Game of Stones, under the edge of the roof. Traverse left the left of the hand crack then topout.    Very easy route but good topout practice.

name: Fin S
description: Sit start with hands on the left side of the fin. Work your way up the right side of the sloped fin without using the loose rocks and boulder near the base. A little finesse and a bit of delicate footwork will see you through to the finish.

name: Game of Stones
description: Sit start below the left edge of the roof, traverse on the ledge to the far right - then top out using only the holds on or below the roof.

name: The Gym Teacher
description: Start on obvious cluster under the roof. A tricky and powerful sequence gains the start holds of The Freshman. Follow right from here.

name: Homework
description: You can get a good campus move in then a dead point to some awesome delicate balancey moves high ball moves to a throw for a jug just below the top

name: Left of Center
description: Sit start and climb straight up through delicate moves until reaching small crimps a bit short of the lip. Crux is figuring out how to get to the lip.

name: Lichen Me, Lichen You
description: Sit start on positive holds with feet under roof.  Tough start move leads to nice crimps on face.  Exit up and left.      Room for exit variations straight up and to the right.    Possible extension starting under roof - see picture.

name: Long Haul Sucker
description: Sit (or squat) start using the same general start point as Game of Thrones, right or left of the edge of the roof. Traverse the start wall to the left, using generous footholds, cracks, and underclings.    Navigate to perpendicular wall and traverse left using footholds on the wall and the top for hands. The large shelf near the wall is off. Topout at the farthest left point of the perpendicular wall.    Fun route, the slopers between the little trees on the perpendicular wall can be tricky.

name: Lunch Money Dyno
description: Stand high on crimps between the first and second roof. Huck to the lip.

name: Mental Hangover
description: Sit start to Mentor Overhang.  Start as Booster Shot, trend right on small crimps, gain start shelf for Mentor Overhang, but, keep feet off of free standing block as you progress towards roof.  Finish around roof as Mentor Overhang.

name: Mentor Overhang
description: Start with hands on shelf and feet on free standing block.  Reach back for angled crimp and work up to nice holds on left and right side of roof.  Work right and exit up through second roof.

name: Milwaukee's Best
description: Stand start, right hand should look for the two-finger hole about chest/neck height, left hand can go up a bit to a vertically-oriented hold (both are chalked up a bit from previous use and should be easy to see). Feet in obvious footholds below. Good warm-up for other climbs on this slab.

name: One Two Arête (Direct)
description: Sit start way low (is there such a thing as a "lay start") with both hands on obvious hold on the point of the arête. There is a good heal to start to the right. Climb and top out straight up the arête. Top out has a tree in the way but can be done without it. Landing is sketch for both the climber and spotter. If you fall past the small flat area you might continue down a steep rocky hill. Crux is the start or the top out. Probably a 3 star if not for the landing and tree at the top out.

name: One Two Arête (Right)
description: Same start as One Two Arête Direct, move up holds and top out to the right. Not flat, but a much safer landing than the direct variation and the trees don't get in the way of toping out. Slightly easier than the direct variation.

name: Pop Quiz
description: Sit start on a slot and a small crimp deep under the roof. First move crux pop up to a crimp. From here follow the rail to the easiest exit over the lip. Traverse back left once on the face and follow it to the top, just right of the scoopy-dihedral. There might be a line that doesn't wander out right...

name: River Bandits
description: Stand start, both hands on generous hold about chest-height, feet on narrow ledges below (a more generous angled foothold can be found a little bit up and to the left). Traverse right, some smearing required; very small toe-holds along the horizontal crack here. Straight up to topout, watch out for the slender branch overhanging, or go right a bit to avoid it.

name: Scareface
description: This highball boulder or short top rope has an overhung bottom half and a vertical top half with unique holds. If bouldering, beware of hold breakage potential. This is a new line, and the holds are rather thin.     Stand start with both hands on a large ledge-like hold. Make a couple moves trending slightly right to establish yourself on the vertical face. Once on the vertical face, head straight up for the pine tree.    Give this one plenty of time to dry after rainfall so that the holds don't break!

name: Scareface Sit
description: Sit start to Scareface.  Start on obvious shelf below stand start of Scareface.  Use feet, crimp, shelf, and whatnot to gain ledge and continue on.

name: Slab Center
description: Sit start using obvious hold in the center of the slab. Climb straight up. Once you reach the huge ledge a foot below the topout, it might be best to traverse left to topout as the stone at the topout directly above the start feels loose and quite sketchy.

name: Slabriela
description: This problem will get better with more traffic. Start on a somewhat vegetated slab and use edges and in-cut horizontals. Follow the path of least resistance until reaching broken features above the slab, then trend slightly right. Aim for the outcropping fifteen or twenty feet above the ground, bypassing two small trees on the left near the top. Use care at the top; there still might be a bit of looseness up there. Promises to develop into a classic warm-up and beginner problem.

name: Space Heater
description: It'll warm you up--no electricity required.    Sit start, work hands up the diagonal crack, get hands up to the top and top out.

name: unnamed
description: Start in obvious hole under the roof. left hand gaston jug. right hand undercling pinch/crimp. climb the path of least resistance.

name: Snake Hole
description: Snake Hole starts with an easy set of hand and foot holds with one 'leap of faith' in the beginning, then settles into a nice line of classic 5.7 stuff. A great way to start the day and warm up.

name: The Blade
description: Sit start underneath the overhang. Left hand on a long, horizontal crimp rail and right hand pinch on low arete. Kneebar on the supporting boulder and work right to the arete. The crux is finding a way to release from a wide wingspan. Top out is fairly easy. Landing is kind of sketchy but the hardest part of the problem is over by the time you get to that point.

name: East Face- Left
description: Crux is reaching last jug. Good overall problem, look for the heel hook.

name: East Face- Right
description: Start with a match on a jug and move up and right or straight up...either way same grade.

name: Sexy Hands
description: Crux is the mantle. One hold may be wet so be sure to check all holds after rain. Be careful of tree directly behind you. It'd be better to have 2 pads or more. Don't move around the overhang, go right up it baby!!

name: Bessie The Cow
description: The center route on this rock. stand start from the crimps and finish at the slabs high point.

name: Cow Pie
description: Sit start on the far left side of the boulder and head straight up.

name: Cow Pie Direct
description: Starts on the sit-start of Cow Pie move up and right, reach for the good holds over the lip and climb the left side of the big face.

name: Daddy Long-Legs Express
description: Begin on the good pinch as for Cow Pie. Traverse low across the boulder, finish in the shallow grove on the right side of the face.

name: Urban Sasquatch
description: Sit start just left of Bessie the Cow. Move up to the edges over the lip and climb the left side of the face.

name: "A" Cup
description: There is a lower crux and upper crux. The lower crux is finding proper foot position to reach around nose to hold. The upper crux is the top out. Becareful...there is loose rock at the top and tree to hit if you fall as well as a rock right below you that would cause some damage if you fell.

name: A Rocky Start
description: A rock start is up from A-cup and is a fun sit start its the only small tower by itself we cleaned the route it used to be really dirty. Crux is coming out of the sit start.

name: Cuidado Piso Mojado
description: Sit start under the roof and head up.

name: Deadpoint Dihedral
description: Sit-start on two good crimper jugs then make the crux deadpoint move to a sloping crimp, footwork will bring you to better holds and an easy top-out.

name: Knife Fight
description: Sit-start obvious block up to crimpers on good feet, crux is pulling on the "sharp as a knife" sidepull-undercling. Good jug makes the top-out not too scary for v1 boulderers.

name: Muffintop
description: Start in dirty dihedral with a small crack up to a roof which should be surmounted. Style dictates mantling from as far right as possible.

name: Power Surge
description: Sit start near or left of the start for Sweat and Slide. Use the good foot to propel the right hand into the sidepull. Adjust and make the solid reach-thru with the left hand up to the ledge. Top out in the trees (Yuck)

name: Slick Rick
description: Stand start 5 feet right of Sweat and Slide heading up the seam (fingerlock) and topping out, crux is overcoming extremely slick feet (V1+). Or alternatively, sit-start as for Sweat & Slide and traverse right, the crux is traversing on dismal feet that face the wrong way (V3+)

name: Sphincter Poker
description: Sit-start left hand crimp right hand side-pull, continue on difficult side-pulls until reaching easier climbing. The parks dept. has removed all the branches from the Sphincter Poker, it is now a much more enjoyable problem.

name: Strawberry Shortcake
description: Sit start on the steep arete 5 feet left of the Muffintop Dihedral. Work up the arete utilizing holds on both sides.

name: Sweat and Slide
description: You start out on two small side pulls and start moving up using a good rail and then a pinch for your left hand. There is a dead point towards the end which is hard giving how slick this rock is.

name: Welcome To The Jungle
description: In the trees you come out of the trees and top out on nice crimpy holds that are really good. Sit start with a pinch to your left. Crux is second move after getting off the deck.

name: West Face of Power Puff
description: What a fun line. Despite being only 3 moves it packs a punch with an exciting finish. Stand start with relatively good holds. Right hand to a sidepull, left hand to a crimp, establish high feet (crux) and throw for the top. Mantle and top-out. The general idea is to ascend directly up the face between A-cup and deadpoint dihedral.

name: Arete problem
description: Sit start on the arete. Crux is a long move to a good jug

name: Back for Redemption
description: The route starts on two crimps right at the arret. You make two big bumps with your left hand using an amazing heel hook. From there move your right hand up and top out. The crux is the top out.

name: Bucket seat
description: Sit start climb the nose feature and top out

name: Flamingo
description: The start is on the south facing wall. It's a huge pinch with your right hand and a decent crimp for your left hand. You then make a huge move to a jug like feature with you right hand. From there move your left hand to the undercling and top out. Crux is the start.

name: Juvenile offender
description: Stand start on the left side of the north face

name: The old number 3
description: Start on the right side of the face couple tricky moves lead to the top out

name: Sexual Heeling
description: Starts on the large block looking hold and then moves up using a really nice heel hook and some big holds.

name: Three Across
description: Follows the crack up the boulder on the west face. Starts on two side pulls and uses pretty obvious holds.

name: Buff Sauce
description: The crux is the start.

name: Far Left Problem
description: An easy, stretchy problem.

name: Far Right Problem
description: Crux is defintely topping out. An overall fun problem.

name: Left to Right Traverse
description: Just a fun little traverse.

name: Middle Arete Traverse
description: Crux is the press with your right hand.

name: Nose Lob
description: Start sitting with hands on large nose feature...may need to stack pads if you are short. Set up and lob to the hold up and right.

name: Abby's Highball
description: Sit start in crack, continue up crack until you reach the face which should take you to the top.

name: Bullwinkle aka God Created Gene Hackman
description: Sit start on the trail, up and left on good holds.

name: Hanging Dihedral
description: Sit start in dirty finger crack and up the dihedral.

name: Hanging Face
description: Start left of Hanging Dihedral and strait up the face using the good holds on the arete.

name: Over The Handlebars
description: Start sitting on the trail to the right of the boulder as you look from the trail.. but sit -left- of the rock holding the boulder on its south west side slightly beneath the rock.  Stay exclusively on the boulder (especially your right foothold as you start).  Move up to the highest part of the boulder.   Crux is getting to your 1st or 2nd hand holds.

name: Rocky
description: Start sitting on the boulder protruding beneath the overhang. Move up the overhang and face. Crux is a set of two finger crimps.

name: Tag Along
description: Start sitting on the trail to the left of the boulder as you look at it from the trail.  Move up easy hand holds and obvious footholds.  Move up to the lowest part of the boulder.   Builds confidence especially for those tag-alongs who you want to get into the sport!

name: Beetlewood
description: Sit start under the small roof adjacent to the rock on the ground (north side). Work your way right using good side pulls. Get to the good rail side-pull and top out.   [same start as Beetlewood Direct]  *NO SUPER EASY WALK DOWN*

name: Beetlewood Direct
description: Same start as Beetlewood (V1). Climb straight up the corner. Crux is the left hand sloper pull to the top out.

name: Dropoff lingo
description: Pads

name: JJCF
description: Crux is body position and footing after first crossover. The route itself is fun!

name: Two Pump Chump
description: Sit start on two wider areas in the crack that runs along the boulder and two bad feet, gain a heel/toe hook and slap up left to a crimpy sloper then work up to the right. short boulder, pretty physical.

name: Dynamite
description: Start with one hand in the obvious, large hole and the other on a good crimp. Make a few moves up the slight slab and top out. Fun beginner line.

name: Heel Toe Boogie
description: This is a super unique line. Sure it's a lowball, but it is one of the best lines in the park. Sit start on a low rail. Find a heel and a toe, bump right hand to a slightly worse crimp, and toss for the lip. Topout is tricky but not bad.

name: Toes Up A-Town Down
description: Sit start sideways underneath the overhang. Feet paste on up high. Left hand starts on good rail and right on a small pinch. Huck for the jug about 4 feet off the ground. Swing out and grab some small crimps to hidden pocket in a sloping rail. Match and top out. If you start from the jug it goes at V4. Fun tricky line.

name: East Quarry Slab
description: Easy dirty slab on the northeast corner. Go Straight up to the left of the small rib like bulge.

name: Escape Route
description: Crux is the move to the top.

name: K- Hole
description: Crux thus far is finding a start and getting off the ground. Then after you figure that out, you have to somehow throw into this tiny/painful finger lock. Then work your way all the way to the apex and top out.

name: Lip Sync
description: There are 2 cruxes, the first is the transition from heel hook to bicycle hook. The second is the mantle to the top. I don't believe that this traverse has ever been sent. If any FA information is available please notify me. Until then the FA will remain as it is.

name: North Arete
description: Crux is getting in position to top out.

name: Snaggle-tooth
description: Crux is moving up the small crimpers.

name: South-Central
description: Moves up the center of the boulder. Instead of topping out on the jug, move left to side pull then top out.

name: Nacho Libre
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Hooch
description: SDS same as for Huckleberry Hooch move out left and straight up using the crack left Huckleberry Hooch and the left corner. Move up on good but committing holds.

name: Huckleberry Hooch
description: Likely the hardest "established" problem at Blue Mounds. SDS on obvious holds feet go under the overhang. Match left over to right hand jug hold. Left foot heel hooks up by where your left hand goes. Throw up for the good holds. Get high feet and begin working the side pull rail feature. Up To the roof. Right hand goes out to a small crimp on the lip of the overhang. Right hand in the crack feature in the middle of overhang. Bump right hand to a small horrible sidepull crimp. Get a left foot backwards and wedged in the left corner of overhang. Slowly stand up and hit a small small crystal feature up top and crank all your might off this. Hit the obvious jug up top and its done.

name: Dodge the Tree
description: Sometimes too many trees is a bad thing. Start on the ground with your back near a young tree. Avoiding grabbing the loose rock (cleverly disguised as one of the few phenomenal hand holds on this boulder) makes this climb marginally harder. Scramble your way up, then duck right at the last move to avoid the overhanding branches of another tree hanging over the top of the boulder.

name: Mincemeat
description: Could have been named "Momo's Mirror". Start sitting at the shallow crack in the middle of the boulder and use a heel hook to give you the chance to get off the ground. There are many options for starting handholds- use what works for you (so long as your butt is on the ground when you start!) Work straight up the shallow crack and finish with a mantle over the top.

name: Mojo Madness
description: This problem starts on the arete on the the south side of the east face. Start with one hand wrapped around the arete and work your way up. Find a series of good hands and feet to propel yourself over the top.  As with many problems on Lover's Fortress, the first move if one of the hardest.

name: Moose's Mantle
description: Start by straddling the north-most arete (the right arete, if facing the boulder's east face) with one hand and one foot on each side. Move up a little and traverse left (south) until you've cleared a large shelf above you. With the shelf just up and to your right, climb straight up and mantle over the top (the climb's hardest move and namesake.)  The top of the shelf is off limits. No hands or feet on top of the shelf, though it'd likely make a more relaxed variant.

name: More Momos
description: Prepare a few curse words for this one-trick-pony of a climb. Start on the ground and find the correct heel-hook / sloper / crimp combination that allows you to liftoff to a few wonderful edges just out of reach from the ground. Once you have the edges, follow them for more straight-forward V1 - 2ish action to the top.

name: Revenge of the Ents
description: A full traverse of the boulder followed by a mantle finish! Start in the shallow crack on the east face and choose a direction. The south and west faces are very easy, and the north face is only slightly more difficult with one or two blind moves. Once you have traversed the full length of the boulder, finish by climbing vertically through the shallow crack you started on and mantling to the top. Be prepared to work through a few trees and bushes that scratch at you as you pass.  Any number of variations for this traverse exist. Change the starting position, direction, no resting... A fun problem for the creative boulderer.

name: Unnamed
description: Stand start on good juggy ledges. Work straight up to the lip. The crux of the boulder is topping out. Easiest way is to traverse left on the lip before pressing it out.

name: Down Climb
description: This is the down climb for Red Green Show but hosts some amazing crimps and edges on a slight slab. Worth playing around on.

name: Duct Tape
description: Variation of Red Green Show that works out left using small crimps under the roof to a credit card crimp on the left face. Use the arete and a few holds on either side to work your way up to a potentially comical finish on the left face.

name: Red Green Show
description: Sit start on good edges with a right heel. Work through a couple of amazing crimps and compression moves. Head straight up to a tricky top out.

name: Unnamed
description: Short and dirty. Sit start on the down hill side of the north face and ride the lip until you hit the arete. Head straight up from there. The crux is not dabbing on a small rock that follows the line.

name: Tetris
description: Start on right side of the roof. Worth through the roof using good edges. Make a long reach back, place a heel and match hands. Cut feet and make a long campus to a blocky ledge. Top out.

name: Bernie's Last Stand
description: Stand start at the lip. Make a few moves through some crimps and slopers.

name: Bernie's Last Stand Sit
description: Sit start and work the lip with heel hooks. Finish through Bernie's Last Stand.

name: Hop the Fence
description: Start with left hand on edge on the arete and right hand on a small sidepull. Optional dyno to the lip or use some micro crimps to work through it. Short but fun.

name: Insurance Fraud
description: Establish on the arete and make a big move to a good edge. Match and finish straight up.

name: Super PAC
description: Powerful and hard tension moves throughout. Cool toehook off the start. Make a huge move to either the slot or to the lip. Match hands on the lip, work the feet through and hit the slopey edge. From there, go straight up to top it out.

name: Toupee Parade
description: Sit start low on left hand pinch and right hand sidepull. Make a small move to an incut half pad crimp. Throw for a good ledge out right. Finish straight up.

name: The 4th Dimension
description: follow the obvious line that leads up the left corner on the face that faces West. Sit start.

name: Tesseract
description: Face to the left of 4th Dimension fun smearfest and easy warmup to the area.

name: Ryan's Lion direct
description: Middle of kanzanri boulder

name: Ryan's Lion twist and shout
description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

name: Slap Happy
description: Sit start on the west corner of the boulder. Work up and to about the 2nd crack in the seam from here slap the top for non existent holds if you can stretch far enough you'll hit a nice knob to grab. Fun moderate problem hardest part is trying to pull up on nothing since you can't see the knob. Short fun and bouldery movement make this a great problem.

name: Traverse Problem
description: Same sit start as "Slap Happy" pull up on tiny crimps that are actually really good. Work some good angle work matching feet in the seams as you move along this traverse and up at the other end of the boulder. You could be a lazy climber like "Matt" :) and just smear feet but that looks silly and defeats this beautiful line. Traverse it matching hands to feet. V3. If you feel the need to monkey Traverse it, it clocks in round V0-V1.

name: Ultra Violent
description: Low sit start under the north east corner. Sharp holds, fight the barn-door in the crux, move left, and up to the top.

name: Blue Sunset
description: SDS. Rather short climb on the blue colored south face of the Alpine Block. Lots of exposure!

name: Chosspile Daredevil
description: High stand start several feet left of Blue Sunset. Possibly much harder moves with a lower start.

name: Monkey Wrench
description: Sit start on the big flake in the tunnel, then move left and top out on the north side. Unique movement. Easiest way off is by climbing to the top of the quarry then down-climbing by a tree.

name: Chamber Maid
description: Very nice looking slab. Down-climbing the Chamber Maid is the best way down from all the climbs which top out on the cliff-line.

name: Fiasco
description: Stand start with right hand on horizontal flat edge and left on gaston flat edge with one good foot. A consistent boulder problem with big moves to decent holds and a huge slap to a sloper high up off the deck.

name: Mosh Pit
description: Stand start in the pit. Using the large flat edges on the main cliff climb up and finish by moving slightly left to large top-out jugs.

name: The Prow
description: The Prow is a must-do classic problem for Blue Mounds! Wonderful big moves on perfect quality pink quartzite, slightly overhanging the whole way. Begin on the brick pinch. The crux is the long move to a sloping block, tiny feet for the crux section. Airy finish, Superb!

name: Rock Music
description: Stand start. Climb the south facing wall of the chamber just left of the trees. Easy 5th class climbing after reaching the ledge at 15 feet.

name: Tuning Fork
description: Sit Start. Climb the wide crack with some face-holds over large boulders and a large pit.

name: Crown of Thornes
description: Sit start. Climb angular holds using toe hooks after the first few moves the climbing backs off for an easier top-out. Dab!

name: Red Headed Stepdaughter
description: Stand start on the sloping hold and a pinch in the middle of the east face. Climb directly up while avoiding vines.

name: Right of Richard's
description: Sit start with right hand on excellent edge and left hand on the low side-pull. One big reach to good jugs.

name: Sam's Opus
description: Excellent roof problem with fun moves. Start low on the rail with a heel-hook, make some moves out right under the ceiling, reach a sloping hold on the left lip then throw right to the large jug. Make the big reach over the roof and establish on the south slab using small sloping crimps. Would be an area classic were it not for the rib-cracking, dab inducing boulders under the roof.

name: Crocodile Who Swallowed an Alarm Clock
description: Start on low left hand undercling jug and a right hand down pulling edge. Make a long reach to a bad three finger one pad edge. Move your feet higher and make a huge deadpoint to start holds of The Project of Yesteryear.  Finish on The Project of Yesteryear. Might be impossible or substantially harder if you're shorter than 6 feet tall.

name: Peter Pan
description: On the backside of the boulder there is a bulging, cooler size block sticking out. Sit start with hands on a pinch on the corner and a good crimp. Make a decent reach to an incut rail on the lip. Easy topout.

name: The Project of Yesteryear
description: Stand start with your hands stacked on left hand crimp and right hand on good edge about a foot and a half underneath the lip. Bump right hand to hold just below the lip and traverse left around the bulge. Reach far back to good rail on top. Throw a right heel and top out. The landing is in a pit and is hard to protect. Bring spotters and pads to keep it safe.

name: [Redacted]
description: Wild problem with an audacious landing. Sit start with hands high on the two good jugs, throw for the sloping side-pull over the lip and hang on for the swing. Crux is holding the swing and not dabbing. Top out is still a bit dirty.

name: Chiropractor
description: Short climb with big holds which still need some cleaning. Be careful not to hurt yourself getting off this boulder, downclimb the lichen covered slab and jump to the adjacent boulder to get off.

name: The Gynecologist
description: Same start as the Psychologist V3 only once you hit the crimp on the bulge keep traversing right and throw up for a beautiful jug hold right before the lip. Both variations have been done straight up is slightly easier. The scary part of this climb is mantling the angled slab on the side if you dare.

name: Psychiatrist
description: Begin by sitting on one of the talus boulders with hands on the sloping ledge on the right side of the South face. Crux section is the first section of lie-backs. Do not fall off to the right!

name: The Psychologist
description: Starts low on crimps and moves up onto better crimps and a nice deep small crimp on the bulge. Go straight up to the point from here on a 2 finger crimp that you crank up onto. Kind of a scary committing top out.

name: Ready Set Throw
description: Start matched on the block feature and make a huge throw to lip on the right. Pull yourself over and top out the boulder.

name: Apollo's Arete
description: SDS on nice big crimps on both side of arete. Pull up and onto feet near the bottom of arete. Work a bouldery sequence to either deadpoint or just got for it hold on the outter rim. Hold is good and can match both hands. Work final movement to the tip of point and up.

name: David
description: Start standing on a small boulder, climb directly up on big holds.

name: Gaia
description: Start bottom left with everything else. Continue right, past Pieta and wrap around the other side of the boulder. Climb the obvious line that follows all the way around this gigantic goddess of a boulder!

name: Nike
description: Want to do the committing final moves of Pieta without having to climb all those darn roofs? This route is a bit contrived but sure is a ton of fun. Stand start as for David, once on the large holds traverse about seven feet right (v1). Once established on the pair of sloping edges on Pieta make the final dead-point move and reach for the top!

name: Perseus
description: Begin on low edges and work your way up to the high right hand edge (v4). Heel-hook and make a powerful reach to a left hand sloper, the crux is a difficult compression move while traversing left. Finish on the easy south face.

name: Pieta
description: Begin on low edges and work your way up to the high right hand edge (v4). Match hands on the edge and move through difficult pinching and a powerful gaston finishing with a long reach around the roof to a mono slot (v6). Set up on the pair of sloping edges just right of the slot and make a committing dead-point to a good three finger edge one more committing reach right and a high step take you to the top out jugs (v3). CLASSIC!

name: Rain With a Chance of Boulders
description: This is the clean line up the northeast face of the quarry boulder (the backside). It features pristine holds and fun exposure. Enjoy your first jug because all you have left is a crimp and then slopers!

name: Slab of The Wasp
description: I am pretty sure that this slab problem has been done before, but if anyone has any FA info please let me know so I can change it. But for now, I'll keep it as is.    This slab problem, although easy, is super fun!! I did it probably 10 times in a row!

name: Uranus
description: One hard move to the lip joins with a few more moves into Gaia. Instead of heading around the boulder, head directly up and the point, and ascend into the heavens and join Uranus.

name: F.W.S. (F**K Will Stancil)
description: Sit start with both hands on an under cling start. Working your way up to finish with a heel hook.

name: The Blank
description: Start low (sit) on the East Corner and climb the slab. Cruxes are the start and transitioning onto the slab.

name: Blankette
description: Sit Start 5 feet right of Succulent Pricks, move straight up and fight the temptation to move left into the finish of S.P.    The crux is the first moves from the sit start, finish on the blank slab.

name: Succulent Pricks
description: Sit start on the south face, up on large holds that all slope the same way. Top out at the apex.

name: C.V. (Clearly Vandalism)
description: Start near C.V. up arete

name: H.M. (Heady Moments)
description: start at H.M. strait up.

name: W
description: Start with hands on ledge above the "W". Wing your way over to the arete, then up the east face. Crux is a set of sharp crimps on arete.

name: The Tree Made Me Do It
description: Sit start on the right side of the tree. Work left on undercling rail being careful not to dab on the tree. After you're on the left side of the tree the problem turns into a rad compression boulder with heel and toehooks.

name: Dusty Problem
description: Start up the crack with a big roof overhead.  Good holds will keep the grade in check but it is roofy for a 5.6.  Finish as desired, but whatever you choose expect to find plenty of lichen and dust.

name: Fortress Chimney
description: Right up the wide crack north of Finger Games.  Take a big piece or two for the bottom section if you lead it.  Very short.

name: Petes face
description: Crux is first couple moves. Good short climb

name: Surprise Ending
description: Follow the main crack up the nose and the face to its left.  Easy climbing/good pro until the crack ends and you find the surprise ending.  Head into the crux with gear just below foot level in a nice horizontal crack.  Watch out for the rocks behind you if you fall.

name: Crack Lovers Delight
description: This is the left side of the obvious inset.  Work your way up until you are under the roof.  Find some pro and jam your way through the roof.  Once you are above the roof, find some holds and struggle to the summit.  Crux is jamming through the roof and moving up the slightly offwidth crack to the obvious flake.  Protects well.

name: Fancy Feet
description: Right crack of the inset.  Work your way up the crack until you can transition to the right face.  Use your fancy feet to dance up over the roof and continue up the dihedral to the summit

name: Glacier Calf Moo
description: follow crack up the blackened wall, crux is the optional (and more aesthetic) finish up smooth overhanging face at the top of the route.

name: I'll Be Home for Christmas
description: First crack around the corner right of Loose Rock.

name: Poison Vines
description: Up the crack on the south side of L-Buttress.  Solid pro for leading.  The crux is the last ten feet to the top out.  Another fun Blue Mounds crack that sees little traffic.

name: Power Booster
description: A fun climb to do if you want something easier and are already in the area.  A helmet isn't a bad idea on this awkward climb since people seemed to be bumping their heads a lot.  Go straight up the wide crack in the corner to the left of Poison Vines.

name: George of the Jungle
description: Follow crack up short face.

name: grape vine
description: finger crack behind the boulder between blockhead and glacier calf moo, crack to grassy mantle on ledge then finish crack up

name: Season's Opener
description: Climb through the wide bottom section until you reach a smaller crack off right.  Move up the crack and for an aesthetic finish and slightly exposed sensation, work slightly left at the top and finish on the face instead of the notch off right.  Great on lead, watch out for hollow and loose rock about halfway up.

name: Buffalo Burr
description: Start in the chimney left of Destination Unknown.  Gain a ledge and work your way up the dihedral using the crack.  Crack is short but sweet.

name: Buffalo Hand Puppet
description: Gain a ledge about eight or ten feet up.  A left facing dihedral with an obvious handcrack leads up from there.  Negotiate straight over a small bulge and youre done.

name: Oath of Fealty
description: A very fun and challenging route.  Climb up to the roof, use hand jams to pull over the roof.  Continue to the top of the crack using fists, and offwidth technique or any face features that can be found.  I'd recommend taping as the rock can be kind of sharp.   RCM&W #45, p.43.

name: Cactus Jam
description: Left (around the corner a few feet) of Dave's Dangle is a route that starts with a thin crack, moves up past a small roof (crack splits the roof), and then direct up the face.

name: Diagonal Crack
description: Up the crack weakness to the right of the roof.  There is a short roof about halfway up.

name: The Crack
description: People seem to either love or hate this creatively named climb, I thought it was a blast.  Follow the wide crack to the top.    RCM&W #35, p.39.

name: Crazy Crack
description: A fun route on either lead or top rope.  Follow the crack up, traverse left at a small roof/ledge, and continue to the top.  The climb tops out at a small ledge 3 feet below the true top.  This is a great place to sit while you belay your second.    RCM&W #31, p.39.

name: Purgatory
description: A classic harder route at Blue Mounds.  Begins in a square black niche about 15 feet right of Crazy Crack.  Climb straight up a broken crack system over several small roofs.  The Falcon Guide (Mike Farris) suggests possibly moving left.  Straight up past an obvious 2 foot long roof crack feels more appropriate.

name: Kanaranzi Corner
description: The roofs and arete add more exposure than you usually find here.  There is a dihedral at the junction of the south and east faces. Climb the corner up to the first roof, go right, then up the east-facing crack to the upper roof (which can easily be made harder, but hardly made easier).

name: Pillar start
description: Start on the obvious pillar without use of triple chockstone and climb the face straight up good crimps and sidepulls with a lower crux

name: The Squeeze
description: Follow the crack.  Those not wanting to use offwidth/chimney technique will find many pleasing features within and outside the crack.   RCM&W #26, p.37.

name: Triple Chockstone
description: Believe it or not this is a chimney with three chockstones in it.  These chockstones, and other crack features make this route quite leadable.  A decent beginner route if you happen to be in the area.   RCM&W #24, p.37.

name: Little Ranzi Crack
description: left trending crack on Blue face.

name: First Blood Part II (Shoshin)
description: Start on a corner and climb straight up under the large block at the top following an intermittent crack as you go. Make use of the tricky holds in the shallow dihedral (crux) and if you're still hanging on after that grab the buckets under the roof (these holds are detached). Finish left and up.

name: Lumberjack Crack
description: The Lumberjack Crack follows the diagonal crack up the Outdoor Recreation Comity wall.  Nice easy lead or top rope for a beginner.

name: Cam Shaft
description: Follow the crack through the roof and find some solid jams and some stemming.  Hit a jug after making a few awkward moves and you'll soon find yourself at the top.  If it was longer it might get more stars.

name: Death Scream
description: Straight up the center of the face until reaching the huge roof. Enter the roof using decent holds and surmount it with a mantle-y thing. Feet are mostly minimal and poor through the crux. I have not seen it climbed gracefully.

name: Failing Fingers
description: Start in the dihedral under a few mini overhangs is consistent 5.9 climbing on good holds

name: Hot Flash
description: A fun stemming corner with small holds and a slight overhang that still remains at the guidebook rating of 5.5.  The face on the right side is unfortunately home to quite a bit of lichen.  Looks harder than 5.5 at first glance.

name: The lean years
description: Fun climb follow a crack up and left of the roof then move straight up. Around the corner from death scream

name: Primitive Man
description: Primitive Man is a fun climb on the far right side of primitive buttress starts about 5 feet right of Failing Fingers and goes straight up the arête the crux is just past the middle where a couple strenuous moves come into play

name: Robins nest
description: Left facing corner and crack

name: War Of The Ring
description: Start on good crimps and work the smaller crimps to the nice sidepullish flake. smear feet and stick better jugs towards top.

name: Behind The Tree
description: Northern-most route on Yellow Lichen. Mostly easier climbing leads to the crux up high (last ten feet to the top-out). The tree is gone.

name: Paul's A-Version
description: This is an interesting variation on Pedestal Left.  Use the same stat as P.L, go up a few feet and look left.  You'll see a small bulge/roof.  Head left (towards the arete) moving underneath the roof.  Climb up the left side of the bulge and continue at a diagonal up and to the right near where P.L tops out.

name: Pedestal Left
description: Pedestal Left follows the crack up the dihedral on the left side of the pedestal as the name implies. It's a good choice for beginners or for getting comfortable with leading on quartzite. The crux lies about halfway up after which the rock becomes more featured. Protection is adequate for lead climbers.

name: Pedestal Right
description: Begin easy climbing straight up the middle of the face to the big ledge half way up, then climb the right-facing corner to the top. There is a large loose chockstone in this corner system a few moves into it. The crux is surpassing the first couple moves in the dihedral. There are adequate protection opportunities for lead climbing.

name: Yellow Lichen Crack
description: Climbs up one of the prettiest walls in blue mounds with purple rock and bright yellow lichen. The crux is low.  It's a shame this climb isn't longer or it would be an area classic.

name: Layback Crack
description: Shorter climb up the crack with no real layback moves to speak of - but maybe I did it wrong?  Still fun.

name: Save-Me-Tree
description: Follow the crack up on the right side of Bottom Boulders.  The cruxes involve cranking on loose rocks, diminishing the quality of an otherwise nice climb.

name: Cussin' Crack
description: Climb blocky stuff with ease for five to ten feet then follow the crack and find the crux about 3/4 of the way up.  My vote is 5.8, but I've entered the guidebook rating of 5.8+.

name: Incapacitation
description: Fun, easy climbing on a short face. The crack is a bit vegetated in places. This is the right-most crack on the many cracks buttress.

name: Noseprick
description: Noseprick is the second crack counting from the climber's right.  Polished footholds make up the crux a little over half way up the crack.

name: Third Time's a Charm
description: Start in some foliage under a tree and break through the small canopy and onto the rock face about ten feet up.  From here go up the pedestal and then the crack/dihedral above which includes the crux.

name: Ivy Right
description: An excellent beginner climb or first lead.  This route follows the crack system straight to the top.   RCM&W #68, p.47.

name: Jasper's Dihedral
description: A fun route.  The bottom of the climb is fairly easy 5.6ish.  The real fun begins at the top where you'll be glad you brought that big piece.   RCM&W #67, p.46.

name: Old Stump
description: Starts out easy the crux is pulling the final moves.  The crux is well protected with a small stopper.  For an easier exit work right at the top (5.6).   RCM&W #67, p.47.

name: Easy Street
description: left of prowess

name: Mean Streak
description: Follow the small ledges and holds up to the roof.  Pull the roof using the crack and continue to the top using the crack.  The crack is somewhat shallow, making jams difficult at times.  The crux is definitely the crack section.  Its called mean streak for a reason.   RCM&W #71, p.47.

name: Balcony Right
description: Very popular.  Begins underneath the right edge of the balcony going straight up the crack and shallow corner (crux).  Continue over the right edge of the balcony's roof.

name: No Go Crack
description: Climbs the flaring short crack above the lower overhang.  Start a few feet left of Balcony Center going up the black face.  Engage the crack and sloping edges (crux) up to the balcony.  Finish up the left side of the balcony.

name: Jammer
description: Up the obvious jamcrack which breaks slightly left.

name: The Abyss
description: This wide crack is on your right when you enter the cave just north of Z.  It sees little traffic and is usually dirty.  Follow this crack straight up and emerge out of the chimney above.  Practice your stemming by using the opposing wall on your way up.

name: Boy Howdy
description: A short little route that might feel slightly hard for its grade.  Begin climbing the scattered features directly below the corner overhead.  Get your hands in the crack above the roof and transition to a pumpy layback (if that's how you choose to do it) with small slick foot holds.

name: Bushmaster
description: Follow the crack straight up the big roof.  There are a lot of jugs throughout this section that make the roof very manageable.  Watch out for cactus at the ledge half way up.  Finish by working right after gaining the big ledge, ending on the face of the giant block at the top.

name: The Horizontal Tango
description: The Horizontal Tango starts up the dihedral in between Seduction and Rejection and In and Out.  Follow this dihedral up to the roof and continue straight up or stay in the crack that works to the right a bit for a harder version.

name: In and Out
description: Crummy climbing up the dihedral and into the off width above.  It was a long time ago that I did this one so maybe it isn't as bad as I remember it being.

name: Roofs
description: Roofs goes up a broken crack system to an overhang (crux) and left facing corner.  The crack stays wet longer than almost any other route at Blue Mounds.  This route is a testy lead for the grade.

name: X
description: X is the crack route at the right edge of Chimney Buttress's large roof.  Start up the left side of the crack eventually moving to its right side.  Continue over the small roof (crux) and up on easier terrain.

name: Z
description: Climb up to a crack in the roof (hands/fists)and work left around the roof.  Continue to the top using the crack and face holds.

name: Stonecutter
description: On the south face, start up a dirty leaning corner just right of the large tree.  Follow the crack and edges up to easier climbing.

name: The C Direct
description: Climb directly up past the right edge of the long overhang. A little over half way up a nice dihedral will lead you the rest of the way to the top.

name: Couch Potato
description: Easy climbing on the left side of the tower is the way to set up a top rope.  Not really worth doing except to TR other routes.  No anchor at the top of the tower so you may want to downclimb this to get off.

name: Two Kids and a Honda
description: Go up the crack to the overhang on the left side of the east face. As you near the top look out for birds and thorny plants.  I found numerous skeletons of dead animals so depending on the time of year you might have to contend with wild creatures for a good spot to belay from.

name: G spot tornado
description: obvious crack through roof follow big flake

name: Prehension
description: Prominent wide crack up the center of Table Rock Buttress.  It seemed like 5.7 climbing the whole way up rather than a distinct crux.

name: Puzzle foot
description: is pretty sustained 5.10 climbing the crux is the middle section trying to find feet.

name: Thumbnail Direct (Guerilla Nuts)
description: This route is the most obvious must do (along with prehension) at this wall so you had better give it a try!    The Thumbnail Direct begins in the alcove feature with a steep crack. Although the technical crux on this route is the first few moves, the final half of the route is mentally difficult due to hard to protect moves with iffy wires.

name: Boulderdash
description: Located on the mirage boulder (aka the short cliff to the left of the triangular overhang you see from the climbers parking lot.   )

name: Brianna
description: on the east face just right of the southeast arete.

name: Cobblestone
description: Climb the south face of the buttress, left of a large inset.

name: Cruise Control
description: Fifteen feet left of "Short Hop" Up a left facing dihedral, then move right around the overhang.

name: False First Ascent
description: This beautiful corner starts with series of juggy power pulls into a nice stance before entering the Crux. The feet go away - some jamming and stemming bring you up to a 5.9 move above gear. Mantle out the top, place a small piece, and head straight up on easy ground.

name: Jumpin' jack flash
description: climb is located five feet right of Brianna

name: Knee High
description: Through the weakness in the overhang a few feet right of "Short Hop"

name: Micro Chip
description: face climb right up the middle of a large boulder.

name: Short Hop
description: Straight up over the initials "W.S." a bit right of the arete.

name: Clingon
description: Climb the south facing panel immediately left of Elm Tree Pinch on nicely spaced edges and horizontal breaks.

name: Elm Tree Pinch
description: face and OW on right side of south face.

name: Park Bench
description: Face and chimney on the left side of south face.

name: Hard right
description: start on obvious crack to ledge then protect the thin seem with micro nut find poor feet and move up crux.

name: Off Width
description: large crack

name: April
description: Climb the far left side of the Summer wall face using the large ledges for the right hand and the corners for the left. Stand start, avoiding the roof.

name: Flake Bake
description: Begin standing, use jugs in the roof and the flake/arete to surmount the roof. Easy problem, beautiful vantage.

name: Summer Arete
description: Begin standing on small flat stone, move up the easy arete slab to the top of the boulder.

name: Burnt-Out Candle
description: The easiest way to the top of this feature.  Start in the dihedral and gain the big ledge.  Here you can plug in some gear to protect the 5.5 face move if you aren't soloing.  Be cautious of cranking hard on the holds near the crux since they are part of a detached block (can be seen at the bottom of the main photo.)  Easy climbing to the top.

name: Short and sweet
description: This climb isn't on sun drop tower. It's 30 steps to the north on the west wall. Not sure what that piece of rock is called?

name: EZ Chimney
description: The short wide chimney with a chockstone in the top half. Crux is getting off the ground.

name: B. unnamed
description: Climb the blocky start to fun face climbing above to the chains (may be pulled back from lip and out of site from below).

name: D. Lupus
description: You have several options to start this excellent route.  1) The line of first ascent takes a direct line below the first bolt on a right-hand crimp and a left hand thumb gaston.  This leads up to side by side layback crimps and then straight up through tenuous moves up to ledge and first bolt (11b).  2) Var. 1: Start on Route C then traverse over to the first bolt (10a/b).  3) Var.2: Start on the Alternate Start to Lupus as described by its separate listing (as its significantly differnet and harder than these two starts).  In all three cases, it may be advisable to either stick clip the first bolt or bring a pad and good spotter.    Once at the first bolt, climb up and right to second bolt and over block to a stance below the face.  For full value, stick to the moves on the face and eliminate the flake on your right.  Climb to a point below the overhang where you get a nice jug for your left hand in the crack to clip from (bolt not visible until you get the hold and lean out).  Climb jugs and final crimps on face directly below and right of anchors.  DO NOT GET SUCKERED INTO THE MUNGY, ROTTEN CORNER AT YOUR LEFT--FINISH EITHER DIRECTLY THROUGH THE ANCHOR OR SLIGHTLY TO ITS RIGHT!

name: E. Alternate Start to Lupus
description: This bouldery start presents thin edging and open-hand strength taking you to the jug, described for Lupus, at 15 feet.  Follow Lupus to the top.

name: G. Familiarus
description: "G" on the grid/photo.  Left hand finish from the start of G/H.  Fun edges and some big moves near the big flake.  Nice overhang pull at the top.  No top anchors yet.  There is a rope with some biners used as a top anchor but it's old-- don't use it.  Rap off the top bolt, or top it out.

name: H. Foxy
description: The right hand finish of G/H on the grid/topo photo.  The FA artist envisioned topping it out directly above the last bolt (see comment below).  You can also climb up the gulley but it's dirty.

name: K. Latrans
description: Originally 11b until a key hold broke.  Now much more technical and demanding, but even better!  Start on the right side of the slab (for full value avoid crack in corner) and dance your way towards the hanging niche above.  Boldly forge upwards via a shallow 2-finger pocket leading to a hidden "thank-God" bucket and on to another left of the camoflauged anchor.  Rappel hangers exist along this route to back off if its not your day.

name: L. Rufus
description: Start as for Latrans but veer right after second bolt and large sidepull to a rising traverse (potentially some dirty or loose stuff) to a stance below the ominuously overhanging and thin face above.  Excellent, technical and sequency moves lead to twin underclings and a sustained finish (hint: gun for a softball sized hold over and down from the chained anchor, but don't stop there....forge boldly to lip and a hidden clipping hold on slab beyond the lip for full value and an easier clip.     Camoflauged chains drop over the lip---don't clip around the chain, but through the links themselves if no fixed biners are present!  Otherwise, leave the biners there, please.  Rapell hangers exsit along this route to back off the route (do not get lowered through them please.

name: P. Alternate Finish for Room with a View
description: Start as per Room With a View, but instead of trending left to the scooped face, charge driectly up the face towards an obvious 1-foot overhang of discolored rock.  Finish as per Room With a View.  There are still still oose sections here and there on this and the Parent route, but more work is being doen to finish its cleaning and bolting process.  Stay tuned.

name: The Avery Traverse
description: SDS in the hand crack on the south face.  Follow it till it ends on the north side of the boulder and top out.  Fun warm up high off the ground

name: Becoming A Victim
description: Start right hand on a decent side pull and left on small two finger crimp.  Work your feet up and make a dynamic move to a small crimp.  Work your feet up again and go for the jug at the lip.  Finish with the easy top out.  Crux is catching the crimp and moving off of it.

name: Fresh Fingers
description: Sit start with your left hand on a crimp, right hand undercling pinch, and anything you can find for feet.  Shoot your left hand to a poor half pad two finger pocket.  Then dyno for one of two thank god pockets at the lip. Catch this and it's over just top out.  The crux is keep your feet on the rock after the first move.

name: Hip Thrust
description: This route starts on the west side of the large crack, work your way staying as low as possible without touching the ground, don't use the top for an extra challenge. The lower you go the harder it is. This route may be harder for taller people.

name: North Face  1
description: SDS in the crack which makes a Y.  Take the right hand version.  Probably 5.8 or 5.9 climbing

name: North Face  2
description: SDS start in the Y crack.  Take the left hand version.  Good warm up

name: North Face 3
description: SDS on face holds next to the Y crack.  Climb straight up between the Y-crack.  All parts of the crack is off which force you into some very interesting moves.

name: Northeast Arete
description: SDS on the obvious holds and terrible feet on the left side of the northeast arete.  Move up on left on small crimps and pinches.  Top out to the left

name: rock chunker
description: Stand start on the obvious double side pull and feet on smeer. Slap up to the horizontal jug and pockets to the top. Fun route!

name: South Face  1
description: SDS in the crack on the south face and move up and right.  At the right arete climb strainght up on piches and small pockets.  The crux is figuring out which pockets to use.

name: South Face 2
description: SDS on the left side of the south face. Staying out of the arete and the crack climb straight up using pockets/pinches. Careful as holds will pull off from time to time.

name: Drill Hole Direct
description: This route is a good warm up that only uses 4 holds. Start on the obvious lower drill hole, and continue from a silver ledges to the second drill hole, top out from there. This route requires balance and may be hard for kids due to the long reaches. Be careful to not crimp to hard on the drill holes because they can be sharp. Avoid using the crack in the middle of the face as well.

name: Silver Arete
description: This route requires good body tension. A lot of this route also need opposition. The start is the obvious first drill hole on the slab face move up the left side of a silver dihedral using arete holds. This whole line follows a curve that the arete creates.

name: Slab Dive
description: This route is a hard slab and contains not many good hands. Thought the hardest part may be the feet when moving from the first few holds to above the green house. You can use the crack right by the 3rd to the right paw finger. Also to top out use the horizontal crack.

name: Practology
description: Continue up the arete to the undercling. After the undercling, the height becomes heady, but keep going!

name: Ugly Kissing
description: On boulder left of Practology. Stand start matched on obvious rail, go straight up the overhanging bulge using slopers and tension until a rail about 3-4 feet from the top.     This may be considerably easier when it's cold, I'll have to go back and see.     I escaped left into the dihedral from that rail, but a direct finish looks feasible and should be pretty fun.    A sit start may add a couple of moves, but I haven't explored it yet.

name: All Brewed Up And No Where To Go
description: SDS on the right side of the blunt arete. Using hold on both sides of the arete work your way to a difficult top out.  Crux is the first and last moves.   Walk off/ climb off to the right (you may want a pad for this,you are basically down-climbing a chossy V1)

name: Blue-Green Olga
description: Start with left hand in seam, right on the lower crimp.  Move up right while climbing through shitty crimps.

name: Brewer's Arete
description: Climb the prominent arete to the right of Brewer's Crack.  All the business is at the bottom and then it mellows out to hard .11 climbing (at least that's what it looks like!)   This is an open project so if you are a D-Town hardman get on it, take pics and let us know if you send!    The crux is pulling to the second bolt without falling and hitting the ledge.  The first bolt just keeps you from cartwheeling down into the woods!

name: Brewer's Crack
description: Short but good crack climb in this (mostly) bouldering area...Belay from a dirty ledge and make sure to anchor the belayer.  Fingers to hands...   Despite being a short (but fun) climb, this is NOT a highball boulder problem as it starts on a ledge fifteen feet up and fall will deffinately ruin your day.

name: Bumblefuck
description: Sit start on a low rail, climb out and up a face following the right arete.

name: Climbing in the Brewed
description: This can be done as a sit start, or standing for the unambitious. Pretty straighforward; climb the bulge to a cool undercling, then to the somewhat creepy mantle without getting too much lichen on yourself. A key hold for me resides out left.

name: Funky Bitch
description: Sit start, climb face without the aretes.

name: The Girth Simulator
description: Start head first, descending into the hole climb towards road and finish with mangle back to where you started.

name: Hobo's Arete
description: Sit start on the face holds left of the arete, then climb straight up the arete.

name: Hobo's Face
description: Start sittin with face holds in hand and climb up. (Starting lower under the boulder adds a lot.)

name: Liquor Sick
description: Standing start with sit start variations.  Start left of rock, traverse right and climb up face.  Stay left of arete.

name: Norskeluce'
description: Sit start with hands on flake, follow cracks up and right.

name: Pedals of Blood
description: Standing start, climb up the arete.

name: Pools and Fat Kids
description: Standing start on the crimps mid face, climb up and through without either arete.

name: Slabby Joe
description: An array of sharp crimps up the face with good sit start variations.

name: Social Security
description: Social Security is a short yet powerful route.     It ascends the only obvious route on the South side of the Hobo Boulder.     Sit Start in the crevice/hole with a left hand on a pinch and a right high on a good jug. Very powerful and sequency moves on slopey ledges and crimps lead you to an enjoyable top-out.    Social Security is a very fun route which gives you a lot of bang for your buck.

name: Trapanese
description: This kickin' little line is more or less a standing start up the dihedral, with a fun throw to the last jug.

name: Unnamed
description: Standing start that climbs through loose holds up the face.

name: Yuder
description: Sitting or standing start the climbs up and left.

name: Selective Amnesia
description: SDS on the southeast corner of the boulder.  Make one hard move to the lip then traverse right matching on a poor slopper, using a cool heel hook is key to pulling this off.  Then make a large right hand move to a good ledge a foot below the lip.  Gain the lip and make the easy top out.  Pretty pumpy for how short it is

name: Sex appeal
description: Climb the obvious line up the center of the east face of the boulder

name: Spraypaint Art
description: Start in the two drilled out shallow pockets (I did not do this) and make one move to the lip and top out.  Beware of loose holds, I pulled off a bunch but there is still some choss.

name: Chocolate Chip
description: Was much harder for me until I found the right beta.  SDS on crimps  and feet in the mini cave.  move up using both aretes.

name: Protocol
description: Start hugging the arete with your left hand and your right in the finger crack.  Slap up the arete with your left then bump your right hand up to a good crimp.  Make a dynamic move to a good crimp then top out.

name: Put Out
description: SDS match on the ledge, move up up to a crimp half way up in the middle of the face.  Hike your feet up and gun for the top.  Only two hands move but fun.

name: Typical
description: SDS match on crimps.  Move up using a flake and the crack.  High step then use the sweet pinch hold and go for the top out.

name: Frosted Flake
description: SDS start on the large ledge and use crimps till you reach another ledge about ten feet up.  There layback the large flake for the last 5-6 feet the top out.  This climbs a lot like a trad route but still fun

name: Iron Cross
description: SDS left hand on the corner right in the crack, feet smeering. Bump right up corner, left up to the sloper crimp. Right into upper horizontal crack and throw up to the top nose. Not too difficult but fun for a short problem.

name: Swamp Monster
description: SDS on the face just right of Volume 1.  Start with your left hand on a poor crimpy sidepull and right on a good crimp.  Make a big desperate move to a good sharp incut crimp (crux).  Then move your right up to a hidden pocket.  Gain the ledge and it's all over.

name: Volume 1
description: SDS in the small dihedral/corner.  Lie back for the first half, couple of large ledges for the second.  Watch out for loose holds and moss

name: Alternative Evolution
description: Stand start on the large left facing side pull. Work your feet until you get a right hand, then move right to the arête and finally work your way up to the top.

name: Alternative Living
description: Start in the back of the roof on a good hold that has a lose chock stone that prevents you from getting as much of your left hand as you would like on it.  From there move left to a great jug, then right to a good hold on the lip of the roof. finish by moving up and left towards a seem and following that seem to the top.  The finish up the seem to the right is Hide Away.

name: Corn Hole
description: Start on the weird triangle feature that sticks out of the wall down low.  Big move to a ledge, than pull around the arete and up the slab.

name: Dice moves
description: Two hard moves beginning with a sit start on two crimps, move up and right to good right hand followed by a big move to the sloping ledge, then continue up the slab to the top, main cave roof is on and quite help full to get up the slab.  It may be possibly to use only the slab but this does not add any thing to the line.

name: Glizzy Gladiator
description: Start on low horizontal crimp edge, work through a series of crimpy features. Finish with a large lunge to the lip off square crimp feature. Big low triangle bulge is on for foot.

name: Grease the Track
description: Sit Start low on left sidepull under the the roof and right sidepull on lip. Fun power trend up and left around the arêté to finish same as Bone Polisher AKA Power Play.  Grease the Track is hobo for getting run over by a train.

name: Gumputation
description: Gump is a Hobo term for a piece of meat.  Start on right small crimp and left sidepull. Get yourself to the undercling looking hold and try not to lose your Gump, going for good holds up top.  Once you figure out how to use the good undercling looking hold, the problem comes together.

name: Hide Away
description: Start the same as alternative living but take the right hand finish.  I found using a heel hook was key to making the big move from the lip of the overhang.

name: Hobo Arêté
description: Start on the good jug and move up the arêté top on to the right or continue up the arêté.

name: Hobos revenge
description: Start the same as Scott's Knee, but head right instead of left. Compression, one reachy move, and fun foot beta, leads to a thin topout. You use the left hand pinches from Maggie as a foot at one point.

name: Hobotion
description: First move crux. Gets easier as you get higher. Another excellent addition to the cliff.

name: Human Evolution
description: Start on a large left facing side pull work your feet up until you get a good right hand and a good left hand, then you can either go crimpy or go big to the lip.

name: Jumption
description: Start just to the right of Gumputation on two crimps. with good feet do a huge move to the lip and top out just above the jug out right.

name: Maggie
description: Start on Left hand low side pull right hand brick pinch and with huge moves, toe hooks, and heals work your way out the roof to large incut/jug. From the incut/jug use some slopers and trickery to gain the top.

name: Power Play
description: Compression sit start on the lowest two holds then with the cleaver foot work bump your hands up to increasingly better holds. short but quite good. this route is made difficult by the fact that you are starting on the lip of a very short roof.  Bone Polisher is Hobo slang for a mean dog.

name: Scott's Knee
description: Stand start on two good underclings that face the back of the cave.  Slap your left hand out to a vertical hold, then work some foot work magic to gain the triangle pinch jug on the lip of the roof finish straight up the face.  Starting at the back of the cave for the full line is an open project which might go around V10.

name: Slip 'n Slide
description: Sit start with left hand on blocky pinch and right hand on sloping ledge. Work your way through two downturing slopey sidepull ledges to a not so easy top out.

name: Spearin' Biscuits
description: Stand start in the chronically wet crack start hold. Do a thuggy move right to the sloper rail. Spear the Biscuit toe to top out the face.

name: Street Thug
description: Sit start on a good right hand and a crapy left hand.  bump and slap your way up to the jug at the top or go big or some combination.  There is a painful kneebar and the move can be done static.  Also watch out for the stump it is a butt breaker.

name: Beer Run
description: Begin with an odd squat-start. Traverse out to the right across the face of the boulder. Very little help from your feet for the first third of the route while hands move across crimpy ridges ac foot or two down from the top of the boulder. Take a short rest when you hit the nice dihedral platform to stand on, then keep moving right to link up with the last few moves of Double Rainbow to finish.Not sure if this route is in local guides but it's the first line I saw when approaching the Bluff Boulder.

name: Discrete Mathematics
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Stand start on a cool undercling. Shorter people might have to use the boulder to get into the undercling. Get established on the wall, then throw big to the lip or crimp your way up the face. Press out the mantel finish."

name: Double Rainbow
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Sit start on a variety of crimp flakes. Double bear hugging arete climbing to a juggy top out."

name: Double Take
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Sit start same as Short Stack but head left to a triangle slot. Traverse along this slopey ledge until you can top out."

name: High Road
description: Variation on Beer Run set by Micheal Spear. Same start as Beer Run but instead of smearing your feet low across the rock, climb up and across using the handholds as feet. Keep your hands off the top and upper ridge of the boulder and balance your way across with hands and feet very close together. Stay high all the way across the front face until meeting up with the last few moves of Double Rainbow.

name: Punchcard
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Sit start on the boulder in crimps on a hairline crack. Go up to a super cool small block pinch, then work up and right to an easy top out."

name: Short Stack
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Sit Start on an array of crimps. Hit a good ledge on the arete then top out on slopers."

name: Smokey the Bear
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Stand start on some slopers. Climb up big slopey ledges to a nice top out."

name: Systems of Equations
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Stand start on a left sidepull, a shart crimp, or a triangular slot. Powerful moves head straight up to another mantel top out. Don't work into the arete."

name: Take Five
description: Shortcut variation on Beer Run. Same start, feet smear across with hands up higher on crimpy ridges. After you hit the dihedral platform for your feet, climb up and slightly to the right to top out (same as Smokey The Bear) rather than continuing on to the Double Rainbow linkup finish.

name: Titanium Milk
description: Visualized and named by Brandon W. Squat start on a left hand sidepull and a right hand crimp, left foot placed on a ledge and right foot placed on a small flake. Left move out to the triangle pocket followed by a foot move up leads to a fun dynamic move up to the solid jug (thus the name). Possibly climbed before, but a good warmup on a seldom used face of the boulder.

name: Whitewater
description: From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering, "Sit start same as Double Rainbow but follow a series of good holds around the left side of the arete."

name: The Art of Peer Pressure
description: Sit start on sloping crimp rail. Trend left into good holds followed by some crimps. Gain the jug ledge and finish the same as "Pressing Matters".

name: Minute Made
description: Sit start on sloping crimp rail. Compress your way up between good side pulls. Finish straight up.

name: Pressing Matters
description: Start low on good right hand side pull and left hand crimp. Slap up and left to a dishy sloper, and then gain the left arete. Work your way to the crimp seam that trends diagonally right. Follow this seam to the jug ledge. Then use some cool overhead press and mantle, or go huge to the jug at the lip. Either way, don't go right into the finish of Minute Made.

name: Fake GOP Ballot Box
description: Start compressing on 2 holds. Staying on the face, move up to a pinch, then our right to a good ledge. Make a large move up to a bad slot, then use the large ledge to the right to make a big move to the top ledge and drop off. Mantling the ledge and toping the face is R/X and not recommended.

name: Manchurian Candidate Direct
description: Start on side pull and crimp left of arete. Work up using an undercling. Get established prior to making the big move around the arete to the jug. What follows is my favorite part as you are forced to make big moves between good holds.  Commitment = Key Once you hit the jug rail you’ve got a few options 1) solo to the top: please don’t do this 2) jump down onto a pile of pads: a fine approach 3) hand traverse right and down climb the corner: would recommend

name: Manchurian Candidate Left
description: Sit start 10 feet left of the arete on the jug left facing sidepull with a good left foot. Move up and right to the arete and into Manchurian Candidate Direct.

name: Manchurian Candidate Right
description: Start the same as "Fake GOP Ballot Box" generally moving up and left, hint - heel hook was used - until a decent left hand crimp is reached. From here go up in a direct fashion avoiding the jug flake on the standard variation. (I know, I know I'm telling you to avoided something here, isn't that an elimination?  No! Because it would be really lame if you went that far right, rested, then backtracked to the top. Sure you could do it... but, why?).
The big offwidth. The Fa did a complete rotation climbing this.

name: Off Charlie
description: I stand start this route, but there is an option to sit start. Lay back the flake and finish straight up.

name: Sinners in the Hands of an Angry God
description: form peters guide to duluth bouldering "Sit start on big ledge on arete. Pull a couple of moves on arete and then head right on some crimps to gain a sharp ledge. Head strait up powerful moves to the top out."

name: Gumby
description: Follow the crack up and right.  The first couple moves are on bomber holds the you are required to use a decent sloper and make a big move out right to a good hold (the crux), then its all over

name: Gumby Variation
description: Start on Gumby and traverse left half way crimping the horizontal seam t the lft arete then top out.

name: Left arete
description: Climbs the right side of the arete.  Start with a crimp for your right and slap your left up the arete till you find a decent spot.  Dyno for the sloper then top out

name: Warm Up Rail
description: Climb the rail up and the right, don't fall off into the tree.  This would be really sweet if you didn't have a ledge for your feet

name: Warm Up Slab
description: climb the obvious slab

name: ASP3
description: The slab just right of the hand crack - this is pretty fun and worth while.  Thin climbing up crimps to a mildly dicey top out.

name: The Hand Crack
description: Climb the hand crack...pretty simple, huh?

name: Loosey-Goosey
description: Highball boulder. Start on the right side of the large wall, move straight up above the large loose-looking rock. Mantle on top, then move left to the top. May require the use of a tree to top out.

name: One ledge, two ledge
description: Start out on the left corner of the large wall and crimp up to a ledge followed by a second ledge. Top out farther right, may require the use of a tree to top out.

name: Outpost 31
description: Climb the crack with use of the arete across the archway.  Easy climb with the opportunity to practice different techniques.

name: Pounder's Crack
description: Standing start on a straight forward crack and face climb.

name: Pounder's Other Crack
description: Finger crack / Face climb between Pounder's Crack and the hand crack...pretty straight forward but fun.

name: Pucker
description: Standing start at an arete and throw for the horizontal.  Gain that then stick to the thin slab and don't think about falling!

name: The Vagina Monologue
description: Standing start on the little seam...climb up using the seam and face.

name: Valley Forge
description: "Stand start on slopers. The slopey bottom ledge is on. Follow the large water runnel to the top." Description from Pete's Digital Duluth Bouldering Guide. It's all about shoe friction and body positioning on the slab/slopers.

name: Where Lovers Lay
description: Very thin line that has been sitting there just waiting to be seen. You will start with a left hand sidepull near (but not in) the large crack and right hand on an arrowhead looking hold. Move slightly right and straight up. You will not use the main large crack at all as you move far enough right that it wouldn't be close enough to be helpful. Look for a small crimp and a really cool press/mantle move.

name: The Golden Doe
description: SDS with undercling/sidepull to the right of the arete and work up the crack holds and to the left into the face leading into the flaring crack that will take you to the top. Once topping out you will trend to the right to use the same finish at the V1 next to it. A straight up finish might be possible, but would up the sketch factor quite a bit.

name: I'm Lichen It
