description: Clean, fun line on good rock. Start on the starting holds for the v6  then head up and right, following the crack. The top out is relatively easy but a fall would be awkward and could be somewhat dangerous if there isn't enough pads.

name: Kitty Litter
description: Pretty basic line that leads up the small crack. This is the first line you will hit when walking in, on the upper cliff band. SDS with 2 sidepulls and move on up using other sidepull holds. Really good positive holds and the top in the tricky part requiring some fancy footwork and a mantle.

name: Morning Slug
description: Sit start with left hand on undercling and right on crimp. Move up to another crimp or straight into big hold in dihedral. Climb up and out the mini roof. Several ways to finish it, but the direct up the face without using the huge crack off to the right is the most fun.

name: Organic Matter
description: Located on the upper band, you will see this one right away. There's a tree right at it, but is easy to avoid the dab. Sit start with left hand on longish rail and right hand on large pinch thing coming out of the wall. High right foot will let you rock up and get into the crack that will lead up and to the left. An easier start is right hand on the longish rail and left hand on super nice sidepull in other crack.

name: Pig-Pen
description: Super fun line following the arching arete. Sit start with both hands on big hold and move up to using sloping features on the arete and some so-so feet on the face. The top is where the business is located.

name: Project #2
description: Another project line that needs to be sent. Get after it.Start way left on the face on obvious jug hold and traverse right and up using some sweet sidepulls, crimps, and an amazing undercling.

name: Short Stack
description: SDS with hand jamming in huge feature and other hand on left arete. Make your way up to big hold on the face and then hop to the top.

name: SKT
description: Fun little traverse line. Start way left and go all the way till you hit the crack system heading up towards a smallish tree. I didn't clean the top of the line as it would require a ton of clearing of dirt/etc and it's simply not worth it to do that much cleaning just to top this out, especially since the traverse aspect is really what this line is all about.  Side note, the landing under it has seen some erosion over the last year and could use some love to make it more user friendly.

name: Sleepy PeePee
description: Fun little line that has an obvious start with the slots in the horizontal crack that is maybe hip high or so. Move up to the rail and then start navigating squeezing both aretes. The rock is gritty, so that's awesome, but getting the feet up is the main challenge.

name: Chump Unknown
description: Start on Stump Chump (or just stand using the bomber undercling and huge left sidepull). Work up a move or two, then use that core strength to press into a wicked double gaston. Fancy footwork bring one into the shallow wanna-be dihedral to the right of the arete, and perhaps another gaston. Either stay in the shallow area, or utilize the arete on the left. Both exits make this semi-traverse the most classic line on the First Street Boulder (in my silly opinion).

name: Chump's Adventure
description: Start the same as Chump Unknown but instead of finishing in the shallow dihedral continue into the starting crimps on unknown #3 problem finishing with the fun dyno.   Adds a more difficult finish to Chump Unknown making it a solid V5 in my opinion.

name: Crimper's Delight
description: Sit start on obvious jug ledge. Make a left hand move to the rail and match. Big move to small crimp, shuffle feet, and proceed to send.

name: Crimper's Right
description: Same Start as delight. Move right to decent sloper. Stand up and finish

name: Crimper's Traverse
description: I don't know if this has been done before so I won't take credit for it. Awkward sit start at Crimper's Delight (right side of boulder) and work left on good rails and crimps until you top out at the left arete, the same top-out as Chump Unknown. The crux for me was the last move because of how long the boulder is, but it's super fun!

name: First Street Fist Fight
description: Feels more like a scramble than a climb. Straight up the slab face to the top.

name: Rocket's Revenge
description: Just left of Stump Chump...Start on the holds on and left of the horizontal and climb the crimps to the top.

name: Stump Chump
description: Sit start on the obvious arete and climb up left of the arete.

name: Teabag
description: Standing start low on two flakes, dynamic moves take you to the top.

name: Unknown
description: Starting at the horizontal  above a cresent dish, climb up  using the diagonal seam.  Seam can also be aided at C2.

name: Unknown 4
description: Same start as Unknown 3, but move towards the arete and then to top.

name: Unknown 7
description: Route #7 in the Urban Cragger. Just to the right of The dihedral warm up problem. Stand start using slot and sloped rail. High feet and use diagonal seam to the top.

name: Unknown 8
description: Start on the corner, move right and up into the shallow dihedral.

name: Yuder's Slab
description: Stand start with small hands up to a slopey hold. Super slabby and really fun!

name: (project) The Sound Of The Life Of The Mind
description: start on the right arete on traverse the horizontal crack into the direct version of this problem.

name: Skeeter Snack
description: the right of the two cracks on the boulder.  Lie back the rail till it ends.  use a poor slopper and high feet to get to the horizontal crack then top out.  Easier for taller folks.

name: The Sound Of The Life Of The Mind (direct)
description: SDS Head straight up the bulge.  Good start holds turn to poor crimps quickly.  Very technical. Took months for me to figure out the Beta.

name: Sticky Foot
description: follow the left crack.  pretty mellow till the top where the crack flares a bit and you must smear with you feet.

name: The Wambulance
description: Follows the arete.  SDS A few big moves to start until a ledge is reached half way up.  from there its cake

name: Aiden's Great Escape
description: Sit start under small bulge and climb up slightly overhanging rock on good holds and lousy feet.  Then move out left and top out.

name: Black from the Back
description: Match crimp to upper crimp to finsh on crack , completely linear route, topout horn by Dudeus maximus.

name: Deer Run
description: Great holds but a bit of a sketchy top out with the trees behind you.

name: Ditry Harry
description: The crux is starting this.  sit sart matched on slopper and lousy feet and bump up and left.  match stem left and hit the next good hold out left and its over just top out.  The crack is not on

name: Dudeus Maximus
description: Start: match on credit card crimp up to intermediate sloper/crimp, up to large shelf hold to top out horn area.

name: Easy on the eyes
description: This takes the line straight up the steepest part of the wall.  The crux half way up way you must match on a sloppy rail and move off of it.

name: Ghetto Coolade
description: Start with a pinch on the start hold of Aiden's great escape and a crimp on your right. Bump to triangle on right up to the rail. Over to the bomber lip on left corner up to the sidepull, sloper and top out....It's less confusing when you see the face of the climb, mainly a sart to straight up..

name: The High Road
description: SDS under the small overhang with your feet on the low angle slab.  use a big sloppy pinch in the mini cave and a small crimp above it and move up and to the left for couple move on nice big holds.  Then traverse right making a big lunge to a big ledge on Aiden's great escape and top out the same as that problem.  A nice warm up with fun moves.

name: Nex Cado
description: Sit start on a small ledge using good side pulls.  Trend right till our about ten feet up and then reach way out left for a small side pull.  Fancy footwork allows you to reach ever father left to a better side pull.  Match on this then throw up to the sloppy rail and then straight up using what ever you can to top out.

name: Of Mice and Men
description: Start the same The High road but move right only a couple feet off the ground.  The hand holds are decent but there is some hard heel hooking.  Tranverse into and finish the same as Ghetto Coolade.

name: Hawk Rock
description: Sit starts all along bottom of rock along shelf then follow multiple holds to the top.

name: Perspective
description: Super fun lip traverse line! Amazing texture and neat holds make this heel hook heavy line a must check out kinda line. Crux is toping out from the jug hold to the uber blank slab top. Good luck!

name: Project Line
description: Project line that I haven't messed with a whole lot yet, so the grade is a total guess. Sit start (?) moving up to the horn corner of the lip and traverse to the jug holds near the middle of the lip and top out same as "perspective."

name: The Big Kahuna
description: This is the big cheese in Lincoln Park. Send this beautiful blank face, and secure your place in history. Good luck.This has had a running start ascent, but if you can do it static using only the face, you may be the first.

name: Easy crack
description: Just go up. Use the crack.

name: Lincoln’s Crack
description: Finger crack bottom to top. Solid locks all the way.

name: Lincoln’s Face
description: Navigate your way through the nearly nonexistent crimps to the top.

name: Grab some grass
description: Sit start on large rail work up to left onto smaller features, feat smearing and edging. Make a large move to a left hand dish. Situate your feet continuing on big features to the left on the slab. Top out between the grass mound and the huge white tube with a technical shamoo.

name: Uncle Pokey
description: Use mainly face holds to start and finish using arete on both sides at the top. Stay in the middle of the face and climb obvious features, easy climb with fun moves mixed in.

name: hobo ride
description: This route can go a few ways. Go straight up the crack system. Or traverse further left past the drop off and work up the lay back crack.    Another option would be to continue the traverse all the way until the cliff line ends

name: pancake
description: This is a short crack that gets a little creepy at the top because it starts at about 8 feet up.  Sit start the crack and work into a trusty layback with foot jams to top out.

name: Porcelain Gods
description: Start left up jugs and good crimp. Move right at 2nd horizontal crack and using crimp work over to the vertical crack and follow it up to decent top out. The way the slab bulbs outward makes it a bit awkward but fun.

name: squat Thrust
description: From the sit start explode with power to hit the jug. Either finish directly or work slightly left in order to make the problem contrived and more powerful (v5)

name: Bob's Bubble Gum Attack
description: Pinch, pull and crimp your way up the face

name: Cocaine Crack
description: Finger crack below Quick fix crack and to the left of Foxxy Lady.  Probably 5.9 and could be combined with quick fix crack if you are really desperate in get new climbing in.

name: Donuts for James
description: Up the center of this boulder/cliff band. Undercling, step up and dyno for the rail.

name: Donuts for James (sit)
description: SDS for donuts for James on decent holds and poor feet.  Pull your butt off the ground and bump your right hadn straight up to the slopper.  Move into the double underclings and finish the same as Donuts for James.  Adds a lot of difficulty

name: Duluth Style
description: Start on the left side of the boulder on a crimp.  Figure out the feet (be creative) and reach up for a left handed undercling.  Get here and you're as good as done with it.

name: Fox Fork
description: This line follows the crack the whole way, anything outside the crack is off. Sit start to obvious crimp and crack next to it,up to the small crimp up and right off of the crack then to top.

name: Foxy Lady
description: Standing start on invisible crimps to a side pull.  Bump your feet up and gun for the topout.

name: Goatse's Back Door
description: The route is chossy and may be easier using roots shrubs as aid.  The crux is mental as you hope not to fall back upon the steep approach.

name: Grandma Bubbles
description: V2ish boulder problem at the bottom with no protection until you are 10 feet up.  The climb mellows quickly with good protection.  Has seen two leads, two solos and a hand full of TR ascents.  Stout route and destined to be a D-Town mini classic.    There are now permanent anchors at the top of this climb.

name: Inferiority Complex
description: What could be an amazing climb fizzles after 8 feet!  Splitter crack in a dihedral and then pretty boring 5.1 climbing.  Could be a good first lead for someone who is really new!  Not a bad solo...

name: Knappogue Slab
description: Sweet slab climb on dime edges with a sloper mantle on top...There are a few horizontal cracks to make it easier if need be...but you should avoid them for style points!

name: Open Project
description: A few ledges then up to a large bulge 10 feet off the deck with poor holds.  Get out there and send this.  Crux is pulling the bulge and toping out. Grade is approximate, you send it and let me know.

name: Pandora' Box
description: First climbed ground up trad in 2007 with sketchy protection but has had two bolts (plus anchors) added to protect the crux.   This was originally rated 5.7 then 5.8 but people whined and suggested 5.10 (BS!) so we rated it 5.9 so as not to sandbag too badly.  It's a good safe lead now...   Solid start to a sequency and balancy crux that asks you to bear down hard on a crimp.  Follow the water groove up using the crimp to a side pull and then shoot for the horn!  Climb mellows above for 15/20 feet to the anchors.

name: Quick Fix Crack
description: Not a bad crack for a quick fix!  If this started from the ground it would be a boulder problem - but the ledge it starts from is 15 feet up so the fall would be big.  Easy first lead and good for learning how to place cams and hexes...we might use this one to teach!   This would have had a vile name if Andy had done it first...established on rope solo.

name: Return of the Seagull
description: SDS on sharp crimps on the arete to the right of Foxy Lady.  Follow the arete to the top out.  All face holds are off.

name: Scrappers
description: This route begins to the left of the obvious black streak.  Work upwards.

name: Security Apreciation
description: A nice little crack that heads left to some scary blocks which may or may not be loose.  Pull on them carefully but don't place protection on them.  A fun little romp!    First lead on-site by Andy McMurray with two pieces of protection, neither of which was small enough for the crack or safe enough to hold a fall (hence the name).

name: Unnamed Black Streak
description: Stay within the black streak.  If you step outside of it, you arent doing this route.  Start on the large hold, reach for the right hand pinch and high step.  Next, head towards the pocket with a left hand and figure the rest out from there.

name: unnamed slab
description: Slabby climbing the center of the cliff. Use decent sloppy holds till you hit the thanks god jugs at the top.

name: Five o'Clock Shadow
description: Just to the left of Skittle Phlegm...work up the big crack and ledge system.

name: Remember The Fallen
description: Start with a little slab to a finger crack in a dihedral to a roof to a ledge to a fist crack/layback...so much variety for such a short route!  This is the only route in Duluth city limits that gives you better than 100 feet of exposure!    This route got its FA on Memorial Day but was named for the PBR Tall Boy that got smoked with a rock while scouting the start of the climb.

name: Skittle Phlegm
description: This hidden gem of Duluth is one of the most asthetic climbs in town.  Starting with off-width and ending with hands, this crack should be 200 feet long!  But it's not.  The crack is 20 to 25 feet.  The finish is a mantle to a small ledge and a couple easy moves to top out.  Don't let the 5.6 rating fool you...this is a sweet route and may be a touch sandbagged if your crack technique is iffy.  Go climb it now...

name: Smack My Ass And Call Me Sally
description: Harness up, and grab those draws boys and girls, Little Fox has its first sport route!!  The beta...work your way up to the third bolt using some solid crimps.  The crux is definitely the last few moves, suck it up, and throw for the top.

name: Tomb of the Mountain King
description: This feature fell but the route listing will stay up for posterity.  Just don't do it!!!   What looks like a sweet off-width roof crack will end up your demise (and your belayer's) if you try this.  The only feasable way seems to be to lie back the roof crack but this will likely enatil pulling down 12 tons of stone.  If your balls are this big then by all means...   but really, enjoy the view but don't try to climb this.    A cave / passage about 40 feet left of Skittle Phlegm.  It looks tempting but should simply remain a cool land mark!

name: Wishful Thinking
description: Corner system to the right of Remember The Fallen...kind of gross and scary do to the loose nature of the corner.  Start from the upper ledge.

name: backtrack AKA "Beep Beep"
description: climb arete next to tree, then mantle

name: The Blue Jaguar
description: Start left hand on a high gaston and right low on a bad crimp.  Move up on good crimps untill, suprise suprise, the holds get bad 15 feet off the deck.  Keep it together and top it out.

name: Clear Water
description: This route climbs the slab right below the top of what i think is called fox nob. Right variation is v0- Small Yacht, middle goes at v2- Clean Water Slab and the left area has yet to be climbed although it looks promising

name: Continuum Hypothesis
description: Start on a rounded crimp and  a decent side pull.  Move through bad crimpy gastons and poor feet till two good side pulls can be reached 10 feet up.  Make a couple more big reaches on decent holds to the top.    "Squat/Stand start on the triangular crimps and the pinch on the curving arch. Use desperate feet to get you to some sharp crimps out left. Work up to the cool diagonal crimps then work your way right to a very enjoyable top-out. Overall, a route whose crux is at the beginning-requiring you to balance your technique with power. Once the first couple moves are reached, enjoyable climbing on positive crimps take you to the top of this very inspiring wall."         -PETER DODGE

name: Cranking the Crack Pipe
description: Start on the uninspired arete, half way up the move left onto the face using a good crimp and poor feet.  Crank off of this and make the very long reach to the diagonal crack to your left.  Follow this crack to top out.  Really a one or two move wonder.

name: curried yogurt
description: sit/stand start on the right corner arete of the down hill face of the free standing boulder.  follow slopy curving arete to the middle of boulder.  then top out.

name: Decayed Strange Quark
description: Start on the large under cling directly under the crack on Time Dilation. Climb the first 8 feet up to the small roof feature on the same line as Time Dilation, then veer left and up to a small under cling rail. Continue straight up over a small mantel and a finish crux on the face 4 feet to the left of the Time Dilation crack. Don't fall.    There is a large flake (8 feet tall, 1-2 feet wide) to the left of the bottom of the climb that sounds very hollow and might be pried off for a more direct line in the future. Don't use for now, it will probably break off if you do and leave you hurting.

name: Double Funk Crack
description: This double crack is a mixture of face/crack climbing. Sit start with a left hand crimp and right hand side pull. Work up the left crack and move over to the right crack to top out.- potential for more problems on this face

name: Emerging From The Shadows
description: Sit start on sharp tiny crimp in a horizontal crack.  Move up to a second horizontal crack with two more sharp crimps.  Step up and then dyno for the sloppy lip, then top it out.  The arete is off.

name: Fight the Phunk
description: Just right of Slap Happy. Sit start on with your hands matched on the obvious ledge. climb straight up on big holds.

name: Foxxy Arete
description: Great holds and feet make a great warm up.  Be sure not to wuss out 2/3 of the ways up by moving out onto the ledge.

name: Friction Fighter
description: A Little Fox classic and a must do for any Minnesota Hardman!  The most obvious line on the three slabs.  Sit start under bulge on two bomber side pulls.  Pull up over the bulge to a sloppy/frictiony rail and then move your left hand to a small rail where you can fit 2-3 fingers. Find a small nub for your left foot on the slab and pull up into a right hand foot match.  10 feet of mellow climbing brings you to a good rest.  Here you can contemplate either down climbing or committing to the top out.  Climb up a couple more feet then reach way up to two small crimps.  Use these to get your feet high enough to mantle and it's all over.

name: Friction Fighter Variation
description: Sit start under slight overhang on good holds and traverse left till you reach the finger crack (which is not on) then back right and up. The top out is sketchy on thin holds. This skips the crux moves of friction fighter.

name: Groovin
description: Sit start on whatever.  Use crimp to work into a really good right leaning side pull.  then work up and ALL the way to the right on really fun slopers.  I have to jump to first sloper, but longer reaches can prob. just grab it.  Super fun warm up.

name: The letdown
description: This short problem starts matched on a low rail on the right corner of the boulder.  Feet stay out left while not using the obvious side of the dihedral. Then make a move out left to a descent crimp. From there, either slap to sloper out right or all the way to top.  Mantle out as far left as possible.  This is a great problem for really short people being that the first long move actually feels long. Difficulty changes with height for sure

name: Liber Abaci
description: Start on a terrible round rail and move up through two more crimpy rounded rails with poor feet.  Once the crack is reached climbing gets much easier, follow the crack up and right and top out.  Let me know if you send and take pics.

name: Lutefisk
description: Named for the pile of fish bones found at the top on the FA.  Good friction rails lead you most of the way and then holds and feet stop.  Use the friction to topout as the angle decreases.  Do not wuss out and move twords Foxxy arete at the top.

name: Moonlight Delight
description: Just to the right of fight the phunk. Fun little problem

name: Northern Exposure
description: Start on the same holds as Friction Fighter but move right after the first move of friction fighter.  Follow the thin crack around the right side of the arete to the top.  The top out is surprisingly good in comparison to many of the other routes in this area (it has holds).

name: PH Balance
description: Sloper route!  sit start on two side pulls in midle/right side of face.  bump longer sidepull up from start then move into the slopy top out.  For duluth, I think this is really fun.

name: Probability Density
description: On the right side of the Super Slab you'll see a 10 foot vertical finger crack about 8 feet off the ground. Start directly below it and head straight up. Using the arete on the left and crimps on the face work through the low crux to get to the crack. At the top of the crack angle up and left on the easy but exposed slab to the top out by the birch trees.

name: Return of the Nephilim
description: Sds. Try not to get wet in the little river that sometimes runs directly around and under the steep face of this problem. Throw to the jug, get your right hand up, resituate, and throw again around the lip to the next jug way up right on the sloping face. Or crimp yourself up. Either way, a good one of a kind problem in Duluth. Much thanks to BIATHLON! for cleaning this boulder up. I didn't want to take the time because it didn't look that great, but these 2 problems are actually well worth the time! Thanks Adam.

name: Shikidang
description: On free standing boulder. Sit start with nice arete.  Use slopy arete to the left and crimps to work up main arete.

name: Singled Out
description: Sit start just to the right of the small ledge.use the large side pull for your left and a tiny crimp for your right.  Move your left hand up on the verticle rail and right up on sloppers.  good technique allows you to stand up to a tiny slopper and dyno for the lip which is the crux.

name: Slap happy
description: Sit start on the arete with your left hand low on a terrible crimp and right on an ok side pull. Slap left hand to sloper. Two more easy moves and your done. The crux is the first two moves.  Must start very low for full value

name: step it up
description: Climb up the blank face starting on small crimps, left one on the face, and the right on the arete.  Use arete to make  you way to the top, then traverse left on the super sweet lip.

name: sweet as
description: start on good holds at eye level. go up with face holds, arete and cool slopers at top.

name: Time Dilation
description: Really fun route if you can keep your nerves at bay. Starts on the big under cling directly below a distinct long vertical crack. Heads straight up a short slabby crux to the long crack with good holds. To top out follow the small seam that angles up and left (it may be tempting to bail up the large ledge to the right, fight the urge!). Keep your head on for a second crux at the top out. Super high top out so be careful! Not a route you want to fall on.

name: Tip-Top
description: Sit start on bottom left of arete on big side pulls.  Move up into the first crimp rail on the face.  Then the second rail on the face, then use three slopers that follow arete out right to the top.

name: The Tribulation
description: SDS on a great left hand side pull in the crack and tiny half pad crimp for the left.  Move up to a sweet pocket then move left into PH balance using the sloppy rail.  Top out the same as PH Balance.  Feels much hard until the right beta is found.

name: Uninspired Arete
description: Named appropriately for the uninspiring line it takes but a good warm up none the less.  start in the finger crack just left of the arete combine the ledges on the arete and the finger crack to top out.

name: Warmup Crack
description: Great fun warm up for the other bouldering. I have bouldered this but would take gear if you wanted to lead. Some great hand jams and stemming. Very wet the majority of the time. Give it atleast 3 days after a rain to dry out.

name: What's Your Reynolds Number?
description: Consider top roping before going for the send. Start up the corner in the middle/rightish side of the super slab. From the top of the corner climb straight up through the crux on the blank slab with a few bad holds. Very balancey, static is key to survival!

name: Whores or S'mores
description: Start on Start stemming facing Warm up crack without using the crack (yeah I know).  Move onto the right using the diagonal crack then move back to the left using the crack and top out the same as warm up crack.  The crux is establishing yourself onto the face.

name: Wonder Drug (AKA Vitamin A)
description: Sit start on a bomber undercling and poor feet.  Move up and left the arete using slopers and crimps.  When your over the center of the boulder top out.  Don't wuss out and move out to the right.

name: charcoal in the ruff
description: Sit start on the farthest right side of the alian wall.  Either matched or with left had out in side pull slot. then move out to horizontal crack on face, or stay on faint arete. go up to large crack using cool sloping holds.  you could continue on the arete line for a harder scarier top out. maybe contrived but fun

name: Close Encounters of the Trad Kind
description: Start with an impossibly small crimp and a dish for your thumb, with feet on the huge ledge. A couple desperate moves deposit one into the amazing hand crack that finishes Flight of the Navigator. Time for the crimping men and women to pull out some traditional skills and jam to the top! Fun through and through!

name: E.T.
description: Start at the giant flake and climb out the hands crack to the right and around the corner.

name: Flight of the Navigator
description: Start on the left side of the giant flake, move up through the little roof and out onto the bomber hands crack. Breathe it out to the top and you're good to go.

name: Predator
description: This is a lesson in thin techniqual climbing, which is much different then its neighbors. Stand start on crimps on the seam that moves up and to the right.  Move up and right to a horizontal seam.  Some techniqual foot work allows you to make a big move to another horizontal seam.  More good foot work allows you to go for a crimp out left, fall here and you'll land on the small tree.  Make one more big move up and right back into the seam to a decent hold and then top out the slab.

name: Sigourney Weaver
description: Work around the giant flake below the start of the crack (either left or right, though left seems to put one in a harder position). Lay back or finger lock if you can get them in; rattly at places as well. Hold it together with some good footwork and you're free into the trees that gaze over the top of this wall. Exit to the right down a shallow gully.

name: Arete's Syndrome
description: Start with a hold on the face and a fish hook on the arete. With high feet on the face, throw out left to a poor sloper. Work the arete and feet to a desperate crimp that really can only be used for balance. Fire for the jugs and the top out is yours.

name: The Bipolar Traverse
description: Start on Prozac Crack till you hit the horizontal crack.  Move right on slopers and ok feet, the pump builds just as you hit the crux.  Finish on Loathing Arete.  The crux of this is really establishing yourself on coner and then moving around onto loathing arete.  Sending this is an immediate cure for your depression.

name: Dyno Project
description: Jump start (unless you're Justin or Soren) to the extremely sharp starting holds on the rail. Dyno up to the right to the jug.

name: Loathing Arete
description: Sit start using left face hold and right arete.  With the right wall off limits, work your way up into the double arete through the overhang.  Top out before your depression causes you to make a poor decision.

name: Prozac crack
description: A nice little 5.9ish jam crack on the left side of the Depression Wall (wall that is just right of the Ultimate Wall).

name: Slabadabadoo
description: Start the slab fest on some pretty positive crimps to a solid jug.  Now to the business.  Get your feet set for a few committing moves on some tiny crimps to a ledge.  Pull past the ledge (don't look down) to a thin diagonal crack.  Use it to top out!

name: Cool 1
description: Stand start with hands on obvious start hold mixture at chest level.   Move out left to cool vertical crimp then use sloping crimp and the sloping arete to the the top.

name: Cool 2
description: Start on same holds as "Cool 1" but move out right to a good hold.   Hit the gaston and rock up to the nice rail above.  Use slopers straight up to mantle out.   A more difficult sit start would go for this one.

name: Foxx's Den
description: Stand start on crimps and climbs straight up on, suprise, more crimps plus a horizontal crack

name: Off Route
description: This takes the obviouse line up the front side of the boulder as you walk at it from the Whatever Wall.  Start on crimps at eye level then move up to awesome vertical crack that continues to top.

name: Off Route (sit)
description: SDS on decent holds low and to the left off the start holds for off route.  Make a big right hand move to the start of off route and continue from there

name: Tick Tack Toe
description: Same start as Cool 2, but continue right into small gully.  Then find your way up using good holds.

name: Up and Coming
description: Stand start move up on slopey holds till you reach the positive horizontal crack (beware of the loose death block wedged in the crack).  top out up and to the right.  As this cleans up it may get better but mossy for now

name: The Powers That Be
description: The Powers That Be is a very unique climb that follows the prominent deep groove.     A perfect mixture of power and touchy-ness is needed for this very deceiving line. What looks to be a nice slabby climb with a very large feature is, instead, a tough route that is bound to be a great project for people.     A sit start on an obvious block below the groove brings you straight into the burliness of the groove. Several power moves requiring just enough technique lead you to the famous high step of the route. Keep your head on as the boulder slabs out. Holds are "on" around the groove, if you want to say. It makes it more pure. However, staying committed to just the groove would be much harder.

name: Climax
description: Make the first move on Tree Hugger to the lippy pocket.  Then move far left to a hidden crimpy flake, adjust your feet, and bring your right hand to a small frictiony bulb.  This gets you onto the Welcome to Duluth project.  Finish straight up the slab using the seam.

name: Climb Called Travis
description: Start to the right of Tree Hugger on good underclings. Move up to the crack on the right and keep going till the jug on the upper left is accessable. Top it out.

name: Tree Hugger
description: Sit start on obvious holds on the arete and move up to a good right lippy pocket, then to the angled crack with thin crimps. Very high feet place one in a slightly crunched position, but ready for an exit, either straight up or out to the right.

name: Welcome to Duluth
description: Start low on crimps that start the rail in the center of the Tree Boulder. Move up and right until a good crimp can be had above the useless mono-pocket, then head straight up without going onto Tree Hugger. That's the idea anyway. A variation could continue up the crack through the end of Tree Hugger as well.

name: Penultimate
description: Start with high hands on one of the holds that start the Ultimate Arete (but just to the left of it. Climb up the slopy curve to jugs and top out. The grade on this can go up or down depending on the beta/holds used. V4 is a general middle of the road grade for many variations that can occur on this side.

name: Rediculously Ultimate
description: Start beneath the bulging prow on the razor sharp undercling.  Move up and over the bulge to top out on Ultimately Pointless.

name: The Ultimate Arete
description: Climb the prow dudes. Jugs to the left are off. I started with a high left hand and my right in the cool little pocket. A lower start has yet to be done.

name: Ultimate crack
description: This is the obvious overhanging crack in the middle of the picture. Crux move is right off the ground pulling on a very insecure handjam. You'll definitely need a good spot for the upper moves.

name: Ultimate Dyno of Ultimate Destiny
description: Stand start with hands on the flat shelf above your head (or at your head if you're taller). Do not be tempted to lay-back the giant solid obvious flake inches from your right hand like a little girl. Be a man and dyno this thing like you know it wants to be.

name: Ultimately Pointless
description: Furthest right problem worth doing. Kind of. If you like short but dangerous awkward V0s. Or if you're just really bored or you climbed out South Little Foxx. Start around to the right of and on the bulging prow and move up on bad slopers to the top.

name: Attack of the Killer Bees
description: This problem is just to the left of the mini-roof.  Choose from the many mediocre start holds, taking advantage of the great feet.  Then throw to a bomber ledge approximately two feet above the start holds.  Use the flake to top out, being careful not to bare down too hard (feels solid, but who knows?).  Fun move, but unfortunately a one move wonder!

name: In The Zone
description: Start with both hands squeezing the double arete. Then move into crimp rail and up into the jug like Killer Bees. But instead of going up, traverse out onto the lip of the roof and top out to the right.

name: Littering And...
description: Sit start using a good ledge for your left hand and a undercling for the right.  Move up to the horizontal crack using decent crimps.  Move your feet up and throw for the last jug of Mr. Muscles.

name: Mr. Muscles
description: Start under the roof and use the finger crack to find the enormous undercling.  Once you've found this bomber hold, head straight up.  Find the little crimp ledge on the edge of the roof and the mediocre crimp/sloper a foot higher and use these to get yourself to the top!

name: Bubba
description: Fun route with a big move at the top. Taller climbers will have an easier time.

name: Jeff
description: Sit start on a huge left facing flake.  Work your way right to two good edges, then back left and up through some painful crimps.  Then figure out the beta that allows you to lunge to a good crimp, follow the small ledge right in to the top out of Bubba.  Fun moves, but not the best rock quality.  Variations:  You can start in Bubba and traverse into Jeff when you get to the mini roof.                    You can also start in Jeff and traverse into Bubba when you get to the two good edges. They are both fun but I didn't add them to keep it less contrived and congested.

name: One Shoe
description: Easy route for warming up or for youth climbers. Can be made easier or harder depending on use of the main wall.

name: Collusion
description: Start with your hands in the horizontal crack at the back of the roof. Through a toe hook and go up the right side on the bolder. keep your feet off of the lower wall to the right of the inflection, it makes the climb more fun and keeps you out of the dirt. After the crux it’s smooth sailing of the friction-slab

name: Impeachment
description: Start on a good side pull and bad right hand. Go up using an even worse hold, big move to a left (crux). From here use some jugs to get above the lip and climb the same 5.8 of putins palace to the top.

name: Putin’s palace
description: The main line, start in the back of the roof with hands on the triangular block. Go strait back using the only hold on the underside of the roof and gain the lip. From here 2 big moves get you comfortably standing above the crux. 5.8 climbing to the top, don’t fall.

name: Cedar Whip
description: Start in the middle of the wall grabbing low and lay backing on the crack. Mantle onto the jug rail above you and move to the left to finish out on obvious large holds. If you stay right and go straight up from the jug rail it is hard and has yet to be done. Don't Grab the detached block as it sounds very hollow.

name: Desperado
description: start on jug rail and make some odd moves to stand on said rail. Slope your way to the top.  Only use the hold on this distinct face.

name: Dubble bubble
description: sit start hands on the crescent shaped crimp with scrunched feet, maybe even a heel. Work your way right and establish your self standing on the large sloper. From here get the next sloper and either elegantly mantle up or flail your legs until you find your self on top   Easier stand start is possible

name: humpty dumpty
description: sit start on a decent left slanting hold. Use slopey hands and bad feet on the rail to gain a good side pull. Hike your feet up and make a very desperate reach high and right. Once you get this hold its over.  A very large wing span allows you to skip the very cool crux moves.

name: Pirates cove
description: sit start in dihedral, hands in vertical crack. Feet off the the right help. Make your way up and left on the blocky features.

name: Toilet bowl
description: strait up the more chossey wall, ends in toilet bowl

name: Unk compression route
description: sit start way scrunched. make a hard move or two and your home free. more information to come

name: Fire and Ice
description: Start matched on an edge on the right side of the arete. Climb the arete using textured slots, crimps and a sweet peanut hold.  Great movement on amazing stone in a serene setting. Classic.

name: Arete Problem
description: The arete on the right of the bigger face...

name: Ditch
description: Start on crimp rail then head straight up the slopey arete.

name: Escaping from Jail
description: Sit start on jugs. Work through ledges to committed top out.

name: Flying Direct
description: From Peter's Guide "Sit start left hand on a high pinch and a right hand on the rounded arete. Work straight up through powerful moves without using the far side of the dihedral."

name: The Flying Wiese
description: Sit start with both hands on the horn and climb through small crimps to the top

name: Jebus Jive
description: Sit start below the big roof - climb straight up and through.

name: Leap of Faith
description: Start low on the face. Head up to slopey rail then left to crimps. Finish straight up.

name: Leesa Lives
description: Sit start using finger crack. Head up using finger crack and poor face holds. Avoid dihedral and arete.

name: Oh Goddamn
description: A sit start that climbs up a series of crimps...pretty mellow

name: Pyramids of You
description: Squat start on ledge on the arete. Follow arete to the top.

name: Shasky Right
description: Stand start on ledge. Head skyward using slopers.

name: Tim Shasky
description: Stand Start on ledge. Head up and left on slopers.

name: Tribute to the Turd
description: Sit start on a big lieback and head straight up.

name: Warchild Pulled One Off
description: Right side of the arete, sit start on crimps. Head up then straight over the overhang

name: Biking In Duluth
description: Starts on the underclings of Top Out Problem and traverses into XMen.

name: Jumungy
description: A terrific V1 sds warmup. Climbs more like a route than a boulder problem, and is almost a little pumpy towards the end. I'm claiming the FA since I spent an hour one day hanging from webbing cleaning this up and making it solid and climbable.

name: New Moon Rising
description: SDS on the far right side of the wall as your looking at it.  Traverse left a few feet off the ground on good holds but poor feet.  Traverse to the left side of the wall until you meet up with Top Out Problem and finish on that.  This is hard to grade as none of the moves are that hard till you top out but it is pumpy.  I will go with V5 but could be anywhere from V4+ to V6 but defiantly harder then Top Out Problem.

name: Stump to the Rump
description: Very difficult start although you have good hand holds leads to a couple sloppers and then a difficult topout that may bump up the grade if you are shorter then 5'9".  both sides of the boulder are "NOT ON" when toping out.

name: Top Out Problem
description: Harkness cleaned up this route (by pulling off all kinds of loose choss). This is a sit-down start on good underclings (that may soon break off) and moves through huge holds with big easy moves and then gets serious real quick with the slabby top-out. The giant loose jug in the middle of the route could probably be crow-barred off to make the route a little better.

name: XMen
description: I know, I know. 4 stars Chris? Seriously? Yes dudes. I'm telling you, this is a classic climb. Here's my reasons: 1. It has a great sit start (a lot of sds in Duluth lack the quality of actually being cool) 2. The movement flows well and is consistent throughout the climb 3. The holds are cool 4. There is an amazing pinch that I had to use (and you will likely not find a hold like this anywhere else in Duluth or Northern MN for that matter!) 5. It's a good enough length to have a little risk involved. Named XMen for the X's that criss-cross the face, the new evolving climbing scene in Duluth, and the mutants that are starting to appear.

name: Completely Independent
description: This climbs the left side of the Upper Wall. Good crimps and a few moves about the same difficulty as the other problems to the right, but shorter with better jugs at the top.

name: Juguelous
description: Climbs the middle of the Upper Wall. Crimpy fun moves to a good and somewhat hidden jug to the right.

name: Made In Switzerland
description: Climb the right side of the upper wall. Named for the ancient Swiss Army sunglasses we found hanging on a tree at the base, which we left and are probably still there.

name: Rock Biter
description: Sds on a crimp and a sidepull. Move right to an intermediate, or go straight to a poor side pull. Fire for the top. Don't get bit.

name: Rock Biter Direct
description: SDS on the same holds as Rock biter and climb straight up.  Good warm up for Rock Biter

name: SOLO EXTENSION
description: Traverse the same as solo mission till you begin to go up Made in Switzerland.  Instead of finnishing on made in switzerland, match in the thin crack then move right to two small crimps and a big sloppy gaston for your right hand.  Good footwork allows you to move to up to some better holds and on to an easy top out.  Crux is getting established on the crimps and sloppy gaston.

name: Solo Mission
description: Start on the most left problem and traverse right through some good crimps and nice holds to the most right problem. The transition to follow the thin crack is the best part of this climb. Great counter pressure move with a crimp in left hand and right hand in crack. Go up from there.

name: Bananimals
description: Bananimals is a terric crimpfest with a deadpoint balance crux. I would give it 4 stars if it was a bit longer. Awesome jug for the last move. The sds has yet to be done and might add a number to the grade.

name: Get the Epidural
description: A neat little crack that requires some finger-lockage and few reachy moves. I thought stand start was V3. The sit start variation begins on a good undercling and requires a little more desperation, so V4

name: Midwives
description: This fun climb looks harder than it is. The wall blanks out for a bried moment here and "Midwives" is the result. Slabby face climbing.

name: Pitocin
description: A good V1 to induce your climbing experience at the PPW. Follow the dirty crack to the right of St. Luke's.

name: Possum
description: Possum starts off the climbing on the lower wall. Kind of a one move wonder, and like so many climbs in Duluth, ends in a slopey topout.

name: St. Luke's
description: Pretty mellow warmup. A lot taller than the picture shows. This follows good holds on a crack that comes to a stance. Continue up the crack on an angled slab or exit right. Left looks kinda sketch and somewhat dirty.

name: St. Mary's
description: Start above the miniature choss cave with a very cool left hold and move on up. A sds to this would be very cool. There's also a possible variation just the left of this that could go up the mungy crack (read: needs to be cleaned) and would be a bit more difficult, but somewhat contrived. Come on out and climb it dudes!

name: Awesome
description: Good holds lead shortly to a slabby topout.

name: Home Water Birth
description: I was tempted to give this four stars since there are very cool holds on this at just the right spot, but it just doesn't flow as well as a four star should imo. Get on it and tell me what you think. Climb the arete and hold it together at the top. Exit rightish. A cool looking variation has yet to be done (that I know of) using both aretes.

name: Nipple Stimulation
description: The further one gets towards the lower wall, the higher the band gets, the more climbing is available. Hence the bump in quality for this one. Fun slabby moves pretty much the whole way.

name: Slab Happy
description: Pretty similar to "Awesome," but a little bit taller. Slabby topout with good holds and some fun moves. 2 variations on this one; you can go left or right.

name: 100% Positive
description: Stand start on a slopey ledge on right side of face. Follow good, sharp holds up and left leading to a sidepull flake. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)    Some loose rock in middle of face, topout is the crux.

name: Better Than a Stick in the Eye
description: Sit start under a line of three large holes. Work up and around the right side of the roof. Follow the crack stemming onto the slopey top of the big roof. Pull over smaller roofs to the top. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)    The flow of the stream can raise or lower the start of this problem, or take the landing away entirely.

name: Dirtiest Dike in Duluth
description: start in the obvious dihedral at the right end of the confederate wall. follow this dihedral up then shoot left for the giant horizontal flake and finish straight up.

name: Evolution
description: Cool, short, steep problem on the way down to the Confederate wall. SDS that works up and over the left side of the face. The climb uses only the face, not the rocks to the left. If you use them, you're not doing the climb (see photos)

name: Fear and Persistance
description: Awkward sit start on small arete. Move up staying out of the crack. Balance your way up the top headwall. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)    Depending on where the water is flowing through the streambed, this climb may be above water. As of 2015 there is no solid ground below this route.

name: Four Course Meal
description: Sit start left hand on slopey rail, right hand on small arete. Move up through good jugs until you get to the huecos. Negotiate the top section with the crack, some huecos, and some side pulls. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)    Depending on where the water is flowing through the streambed, this climb may be above water. As of 2015 there is no solid ground below this route.

name: Gorilla Warfare
description: Squat start low on Arete. Follow arete with awesome jugs. At the upper ledge, follow it right to an easy top out. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)

name: Gorilla Warfare Direct
description: Squat start low on the arete. Follow arete with awesome jugs. At the upper ledge, don't wimp out and traverse right, be bold and dyno to the top of the corner on How Dirty Boys Get Clean. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)

name: How Dirty Boys Get Clean
description: Squat start in horizontal slot jug below roof. Move up to slopey ledge, then crip your way straight up to the slopey top out. Arete is off. Don't cheat the topout by going around the arete. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)

name: Orange Against the Sky
description: Stand start on high jug. Pull the roof then head up and left to the giant ledge. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)

name: Three Sticks and You're Out
description: Sit Start on the blunt arete and work up good ledges left of the crack.  Follow the good ledges crossing the crack to a fun, easy top out.  (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)    Depending on where the water is flowing through the streambed, this climb may be above water. As of 2015 there is no solid ground below this route.

name: Universal Truth
description: Sit start under the straight vertical face. Powerful moves lead to the main face. Use the obvious slots to gain the flake roof. Then dive into the fun top face. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)    The flow of the stream can raise or lower the start of this problem, or take the landing away entirely.

name: A Romance With the Woman of Your Dreams
description: Jump start on a crimp or a slopey pinch underneath the overhanging boulder. Compress your way out of the cave and finish up the expose face. Right main boulder and left wall are off. Amazing route. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)    High water levels put the landing in the stream and makes protection impossible.

name: Butterfly Effect
description: Sit start on a jug at the bottom of the fissure crack. Follow the crack into Snowball Effect. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)

name: Eli
description: Stand start on a sloping jug. Work your way out the bulge through fun compression moves.  This route has some of the better rock quality on the boulder.  Be careful of the wall behind you.  Variation: You can start same as Asian Porn and climb into the start of Eli for a very nice V7.  Hint, kneebars.

name: Goldsmith
description: Start same as Snowball Effect. Do the first few moves, than work right.  Use a kneebar to transition into Eli.

name: Low Tides & High Times
description: Sit Start hugging the overhanging arete.  Left hand on a high crimp, right hand on a slopey crimp.  Work up the arete to a good jug below the roof.  Traverse the horizontal crack until you can go big to the overhanging boulder.  Finish on the route A Romance With the Woman of Your Dreams.(From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)  Higher water levels put the landing into the stream.

name: Snowball Effect
description: Sit start in the cave on a big flake. Work up through the small dihedral in the boulder. Follow the small crack up to a scary top out. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)      Top out is very tall, and landing is questionable. The climbing in the top 1/3 of the route is easier than down low.

name: Task Force
description: sit start matched on the obvious rail. move up and right to gain the underclings then top out out right.

name: Unearthing the Vendetta
description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder with feet on the small left wall (It is really hard without it). Work up following the rightward slant of the boulder to an intense top out. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)

name: Fun As All Hell
description: Starting near the graffiti, climb through the crimps, then up and around the overhang.

name: Shit' Hole
description: Standing start just left of the telephone pole on small holds, climb up and past the middle seam.

name: Tiller's Thriller
description: Standing start in the center of the face, chuck to the horizontal from the arete, and try to smile while negotiating the thin slab above.

name: CheckmatE
description: Traverse left starting on the far right side of the cliff on a ledge just above your head.  move through a tricky sequence to get around the arete and into the crux.  the begining is tough until you figure out the right sequence.

name: Disappointment
description: Start of the right side of the sloppy boulder with left hand on decent hold and right hand on sidepull and trend left to the super cool little seam and then straight up. This boulder has some of the coolest features and texture I have seen, but it's sadly to featured to put out anything super awesome.

name: Gitchigumi Groupie
description: Around the corner to the left of Lucy's Ladder. Start on obvious ledge, to side pull, to double side pulls, and up to crimps to top.

name: Jinkies
description: The crux is probably the start? The sloppy edge/lip hold is super cool.

name: Lucy's ladder
description: Stand start with hands on obvious holds, smear on slab and follow semi-jug holds to the top.

name: Moss Man
description: SDS made a bit awkward by the platform and vicinity of the stream. As long as you have a pad it is not as awkward. Use side pull and strange jug for start holds and move up through awesome features and finish on sloped ledge. Avoid mossy dihedral feature

name: Oblivious
description: Super fun climb with the crux on the second half of the climb after you get the gaston pinch hold. Pretty tall and pretty scary, but a great landing is built. I did it solo since there really isn't room for a spotter anyways.

name: Over the River and Through the Woods
description: SDS on broken sloped rail with feet on small rails. Due to the unique nature or this rock I did not use the rock protrusion just to the left for feet, it is more like the ground than part of the wall and much more fun without it. Move up through big holds and top out on sloped ledge. Cool movement and really awesome features and rock.

name: PB & J
description: Left hand on good hold with right hand on big hold/sidepull. Trend up and left and top out straight up. When you get to the top you can just top out to the right but going straight up gives a nice little mantel which is fun. If cleaned and a base is built above the water this line could start lower by the water level. We're working on it...

name: Reveling the Beauty
description: THe crux is right at the start where the crack is more of a seam more up into easier teritory and get some pro in.  Then move on to easier climbing to the top.  Can be bouldered at V0 R/X

name: Rotten Carcass
description: Pretty fun little climb and I am no crack climber! I ended up doing a fun little bump/toss for the lip and that was the crux I thought.

name: Sassafrass
description: Good warm up and place to run laps.

name: Skeeter Snack
description: Climb straight up the arete between Lucy's Ladder and Gitchigumi Groupie

name: ATV
description: SDS on two pockets and move up using side pulls and pockets till you make a dynamic move to a large jug half way p the wall(crux).  Hike your feet up and make a big move out left to a good hold and head for the top avoiding the crack

name: Cake Eaters
description: Crack left of ATV

name: Escaping the Habit of Living
description: Obvious line strait up cliff band, great problem with and easy start, crux is getting your self established on sloping side pull rail and throwing for jug rail.

name: sketchtastic
description: This route follows up the arete, stand start on flat ledge and small crimp above your head. slap up to higher ledges and hit a crimp on the face. continue up the arete and top out with spotters ready.

name: Lady Fingers
description: SDS in the triangle hold and a two-finger pocket just beneath it. Pull straight up and work up the large crack with your left hand and hit the beautiful rail. Finish off with style.

name: Porky's Arse
description: Sit start with left hand on the corner and right hand on right corner, feet smeering. Work left hand up left corner and right hand up right corner. Top out straight up the face, friction and good smeering is a must. Strong but classic line!

name: Bulbasaur
description: The movement on this plus the super fun topout make it a must. I cleaned off a serious amount of crap to get to this boulder, so you should humor me by climbing it. Pull right from the sit start and work up the horizontal cracks to a beautiful right hand crimp above a mossy platform (avoid the platform).  Straight up to an apparent slope and top out using the deepest diagonal crack ever.

name: Venusaur
description: Sick route with a scary top out that will make you almost wet your pants. Easy start that transitions into a more powerful and technical set of beta to get yourself secure on the thin vertical crack. The crux is getting to the top out because you're high off the ground and your feet feel insecure. There are good enough hand holds and you just have to trust your feet to get over the top!

name: Fancy Dancer
description: This climb follows up the obvious arete on the Road Weary wall. Sit start on crimp and or undercling with feet at or below "ground" level. climb up to crux using a hold just to your right and up to jugs at top. The very top is blank but is easy with large jugs to stand on.

name: Gyro Dancer
description: Sweet friction-y arete climb that can be done a few ways, either v2+ to v3+ depending on height and span. Beta below:Sit start matched on a ledge with a right foot flake, and the option of a far left foot ledge or a ledge under your hand start. Move out and left to a sidepull, rearrange your feet and move on the arete with your right and into an undercling with your left hand. Transfer onto the arete with both hands using tension and move out right to a crimp slot. Bump your left up, match into the arete, use an awesome ball hold, and throw out right to a dish and a good topout using an immaculate left pinch. This route has been climbed direct, and adds fun techy moves to the start and maybe half a grade. This version is definitely more "pure", but you should climb it however makes you happy.

name: Porcupine Crack
description: Start at the far left end of the crack and traverse horizontally up to your right negotiating the crack and feet on obvious foot holds. Traverse fully to the right hand corner and top out on corner. Great climb lots of fun.

name: Project 1
description: Difficult start on a rail and crimp your way through 3 small holds.  Crux is making a huge throw off of the tiny crimps to a decent jug.  sure to be a tough send.  I am only guessing at the grade but i know it's harder then V7 and probably V8.  Have worked this for over a year and gotten no where close to getting it.

name: Project 2 ???
description: start the same as tiger blood but move right out of the crack into terrible rails.  Not sure if this can even be done but just putting it out there.  Would be super hard

name: Project 3 ???
description: start on the right side of the arete left of tiger blood the first two holds are good and then it goes almost blank untill the top.  possiblibty for a huge dyno?

name: TIGER BLOOD
description: Crack problem.  THe start is the most difficult part.  I have cleaned this a lot but it is still a bit dirty.  Good warm up for working projects.

name: Black Feather
description: Some of the best finger crack in Duluth, this climb eats gear up and is a great lead!  If it were longer it could hold it's own anywhere!  The crack proper starts about 15 feet up the face but the bottom is fun as well...

name: The Alcove
description: A dark and sometimes wet crack...not a bad lead but not much to it...

name: Dark Boulder Face
description: Short face with some horizontal cracks. Fun boulder problem although a little tall for some.  Watch for glass at the bottom.

name: If At First
description: easy 5.6 climbing broken up by three ledges, maybe a 5.8 move or two if you shy away from the cracks

name: The Longest Yard
description: Starts near drill hole to right of 3rd class gully. Gets a little slabby at the end.

name: The Lord is Coming Wall
description: Fun romp up the face to the right of Stove...used to bear spraypaint that warned the lord is coming (apparently) but this gone now.

name: Beginner's Crack
description: The crack in the center of the face just left of New Corner.  Easy but a good lesson on crack technique.

name: Bionic Finger Crack
description: Bionic Finger Crack is located on the Tunnel Bluff just to the left of Dislocation Overhang.  The climb shares the same easy first 35 feet (5.5) as Dislocation and then veers left up the obvious little seam.  Look for the little pocket, which will be of little use, and then try to jam your fingers into the seam and pull up.  If you are leading, your fingers will be in the placements and placing at waist level will be a trick.  Try to work your toes into the seam or toe hook the corner.  Smearing seems like a good idea and would be if the rock had any friction! It's short, but sweet and will make you feel like a real dude!

name: The Bulge
description: An easy TR set-up or a good lead, this route follows the first obvious crack line to climber's left of The Flake.  With excellent technique, this route goes fairly easily.  Without, it can get difficult quickly.

name: Cakewalk
description: The Pagel/Kollath guide : Superior Climbs (out of print) describes it as a "flake, face, and jam crack" but doesn't show a detailed topo.I climbed up to an undercling and traversed right to a flake with a wide crack (4"). At the top of the flake I traversed left on a ledge to a topout crack. This seems to match the Pagel description and looks like the most enjoyable climb in that immediate area.

name: Corner Geometry
description: Fun route and good lead for the difficulty. The easiest route on the NW Bluff Follow the right facing crack all the way up. Starts off as a 5in off-width for about 10 feet until theres a good jug. The cruxes are at the off-width at the start and the slopers at the top. The route is a little run out between the roof and the ledge to the right. Rock quality is good.

name: Dislocation Overhang
description: Located on the Tunnel Bluff, start up toward the obvious roof above a big ledge (Bionic Finger Crack is to the left).  Straight forward climbing to the ledge with tons of protection (small to medium cams and nuts).  The Crux is at the roof and requires a layback on some slick rock.  Commiting move but easy to protect with a #2 Camalot and a long sling.  After pulling the overhang gain the crack and enjoy the easy jamming to the top.   Fun little climb with lots of protection for beginning leaders.

name: The Flake
description: A good climb up an obvious and sharp flake that creates a dihedral.  Straight forward climbing but the crux could easily result in a broken ankle if you fall on lead (foot jam, not ground fall...)

name: Jigsaw
description: Just to the right of Dislocation Overhang, this face climb is fun and not too obvious.  If leading you'll need to use the crack of Dislocation for gear...better yet, just TR from the same anchor

name: Locomotion
description: A stemming chimney. Start is a little junky but fun moves in the climb.

name: New Corner
description: Corner and crack just left of Bionic Finger Crack.  Easy climb - great first lead as the gear is solid the whole way.

name: Royal Robbins F12 Overhang
description: Smear and stem your way to the overhang then reach up onto the face to a solid left facing layback.

name: Simple Corner
description: Right facing cornerleft of New Corner.  Easy and not really worth the effort to lead...many people solo this but be aware that it is still 5th class (maybe 5.3...) and a fall will do a lot of damage.

name: Static is a Four Letter Word
description: Face climb between Simple Corner and Beginners Crack.  Easier if you are tall.

name: Take Two, They're Small
description: The crux is the beginning, hard to figure out how to start. Work your way around a small roof and go straight up.  Note: A set of glue-on bolts were just placed for sport (not sure who set them or if they were done correctly, the first bolt is about 12-15 feet up). There was a set of TR anchors up that got used but were determined to be unsafe and cut off on 3/26/20.

name: Two right Feet
description: From Superior Climbs: "Although its not a bad route, this climb is rather particular because it is neither obvious nor direct; its sort of like always being off route. Best advice: when in doubt, step right."   Additional commentary: Anchor up top can be made pretty far back from the wall. There are multiple variations that look more fun than stepping right. They look more difficult than and with worse pro then if continuing right. Would not recommend leading.

name: Waking Up In Duluth
description: Tunnel Bluff South West Face. The crux is probably finding a dry, mosquito free day, but this climb, despite the controversy it may create from the local climbing ethics police will be enjoyed by many. It is fun, clean (for the moment!), and well protected. No "set ups" required.    Pitch #1: Get immediately into the beautiful right facing dihedral finger crack, jog right to a bolt and surmount an overhang (awesome movement!) ending on some slab moves to a two-bolt belay. 5.9, 15m.

name: Blood in My French Fries
description: Traversing route with only red holds. Top and big hole is off.

name: Burger King Foot Lettuce
description: Traversing route. Green holds only, no using the big hole or top, otherwise nats on. Send it in the J’s for an extra challenge.

name: Superhuman Manatee Death Force.
description: Traversing route all the way around with only blue holds. Top and big hole is off. Do iT iN THe J’s

name: Tang Dynasty
description: Traverse on orange holds. No using the top or big hole.

name: Yeet or be Yeeted
description: Yellow traverse route. No using the big hole or top. Wonder if you could send it in roller blades?...

name: Beached whale slab
description: Start same as crimpin ain't easy. Grain decent crimp in left and match. High feet lead you to a big left hand throw to bad sloping crimp thing. For balance Gaston on poor sloper under your left hand. Bring left foot up to good edge and the Gaston with right hand again to decent crimp. Throw your right foot over the bulge and try to find good feet. Drop left foot and bump left hand up above your right hand to another poor crimp. Reach way out to poor sloping seem with right and compress your way up to a scary stand. At this point you have to smear with hands and feet and find your way up the tall slab. Best problem in the area so far!

name: Crimpin aint easy (but it sho is fun)
description: Start on under cling side pull jug. Good feet directly under start. Shoot up with left hand to crimp then gain right hand crimp. Adjust feet and Gaston to decent crimp with left. Do a funky mantle move to gain good right foot. Slowly reach for another right handed crimp. Move left hand up crimping rail and smear with left foot. Big move to decent slopes. Gain wide feet and do another big move to 2 pad crease on top out. Easy mantle top out

name: In the time of chimpanzees
description: Getting to the sloping rail is crux on this one. Start left hand on crimp right hand on good flat ledge. Jump from top to other boulder just below top out

name: Magnetic Arete
description: Crux is definitely the opening moves. Start on single pad crimps. Gain a good foot under bulge with left and heel hook arete with right. Throw for knobs with right and match with left. Pull yourself over the bulge and walk easy slab up. Was V4 until new easy beta was found. Fun problem! Good warm up

name: Magnetic Rock
description: This is a placeholder for Magnetic Rock.  A large exposed glacial rock formation 1.5 miles from the Gunflint Trail on "Magetic Lake" hiking trail.  I was unable to complete this send as I did not hike this trail with the proper gear.  The photo is of me just playing around.  The rating is a complete guess for the face in the photo.  There are lots of possibilities here.  If anyone has any information regarding this rock or climbing it please let me know.

name: The Naturalist
description: Start on good side pull jug. Use decent feet to struggle up a straight crimp rail. Find feet and dyno to a very bad sloping dish right under the top. Find feet again and do a big move to the top out or go for decent edges and add a few extra moves. Very easy mantle top out

name: Route 1
description: I started in the center of the rock pictured, I ended up going slightly to the left as I got up higher and ran into a tree root. The root was loose and not good to put weight on so I would recommend not using it. Decent hand holds, and not many loose stones. Very easy to get back to the bottom of The Pit when you top out.

name: Route 2
description: Started right in the center of the face, plenty of starting footholds/handholds

name: A Salami for Your Boy in the Army
description: This route starts left of Rude Awakening in the crack left of its first bolt. Head up the crack and into the dihedral following the bolt line until it meets up with Rude Awakening. Use the final two bolts and chains of Rude Awakening.

name: Annadonia
description: A tough start into some really good powerful climbing.  The final moves are pretty tough too.

name: Campinini
description: Campinini is just left of Geriatric Sex Maniacs from Mars and begins off of an obvious two foot tall boulder. The crux of this route is getting off the ground/boulder and past the second bolt where the difficulties ease until the final overhang. The start involves tip-toeing your left foot off of the boulder and bumping your right hand to a sloping dish while holding a crimp/undercling with the left. It looks possible, and very difficult, to begin climbing from the ground by using a very shallow left hand dish. There are a fun series of difficult moves through the second bolt where you reach bomber ledges and a good rest. The route then proceeds through the upper overhanging arete and finishes on anchors immediately to the right of the last bolt.    Due to a lack of traffic the top of this route is very loose and dirty. Get out of the way and expect a shower of rocks from the leader as they approach the top.    RCM&W # 69, p. 130

name: Cardiac Standstill
description: This is a place holder entry in the interest of having a complete route list. If you have climbed this route and have details, please add them to the comments or email me and I will update the description and reassign the route to you.    Thanks.    -=glenn=-   RCM&W # 57, p. 126

name: Cinq Jour D'Affille
description: A good beginner route or lead.  Basically just follow the line of bolts. Stay to the right of the bolts towards the small roof.  The crux is about half way up and can be avoided by traversing far to the right.   RCM&W #64, p.130.

name: Cookie Crumble
description: This is a place holder entry in the interest of having a complete route list. If you have climbed this route and have details, please add them to the comments or email me and I will update the description and reassign the route to you.    Thanks.    -=glenn=-  RCM&W # 65, p. 130

name: Cool for Cats
description: Never even considered trying this route in the summer due to slimey lichen cover, which would undoubtedly make mosquitoes even less enjoyable. Climbed it first time on a cold mid-October day and found it actually quite fun. Start on a dark face with two bolts, go up the arete, and surmount a tricky overhang (crux). Quintessential Red Wing dirt climb: for those who want it fun, do it early spring or late fall, for those who want hardcore swamp-like experience plough yourself into it on a hot and humid day in August.   RCM&W #76, p. 130

name: Danger High Boltage
description: Bring your mantling and edging skills to successfully lead this route. Veer right next to the 1st bolt and finish by heading left of the anchors.  The crux is between the 3rd and 4th bolts.  RCM&W # 60, p. 126

name: Dirty Corner
description: This is a place holder entry in the interest of having a complete route list. If you have climbed this route and have details, please add them to the comments or email me and I will update the description and reassign the route to you.    Thanks.    -=glenn=-   RCM&W #75, p. 130   Owl Closure Route, climbing closed from Feb thru June

name: ESP
description: THIS ROUTE HAS BEEN CHOPPED, thankfully.  I'll leave this for historical reasons.    In general, I would usually rather be climbing even the worst routes than not climbing at all.  ESP, however, is so bad that it is actually worse to be climbing it than to not be climbing at all.  I've been an obsessive, passionate climber for almost ten years, and when I got down from this route, I said aloud, "I don't know if I ever want to climb again."  It was bad enough that, for a moment, the entire lifestyle and activity felt like a mistake.  Luckily, I shook the sensation off, but the aftertaste remained.   Before I was assigned the route, I listed a few detractors below in the comments.  With sandy chossiness, ugly graffiti, dwarfish length, awkward moves, rusty bolts, dangerous anchors, awful position, and seepage, this route has it all.  Alternatively, you might consider the length to be a plus - at least it doesn't last all that long.  Woe be to Red Wing and Minnesota, that they harbor this route.

name: Femme Fatale
description: Moist most of the time. Start off the ledge to the left climb to a very "hard to clip" bolt.  Fun climbing with powerful reaches and sharp crimpers/pockets. A surprising slab crux brings you to a "runout" for the bluff.  Aside from the general wetness it's a really fun route and should get more traffic.  Probably one of the better 12's at the bluff. Just left of "Quiet Desperation."

name: Freebase
description: Corner Crack between Cardiac Standstill and Rock-a-holics.  Leadable with gear or toprope using the anchors for Rock-a-holics.  Enjoy the variety of climbing techniques required to ascend this crack.   RCM&W # 58, p. 126

name: The Future
description: Starts on "Geriatric" and follows the weakest line right through "Annadonia" to "Looking For Lust." Surprisingly fun and long.

name: Geriatric Sex Maniacs from Mars
description: This route is located in the corner about 20 feet to the left of Annadonia.  Crux is low-- at the bulge getting to the standing ledge.  From the ledge you can finish on 3 different routes.  This is the left most of these lines.  The corner you climb in for this route is pretty sandy up high, so it kind of sucks.  It would be great if there were less sand.     RCM&W #70, p. 130

name: Last Call for Alcohol
description: This climb is to the right of Rude Awakening, the area is between the Annadonia area and Perfect Crimb area.  If you end up looking for this climb, it's actually pretty decent, but would be better with more traffic to get the spiderwebs and grit out of the holds.  It climbs just right of a tree up a small crack/corner.  Some fun moves that unfortunately are over too quick.     RCM&W # 79, p. 131

name: Looking for Lust
description: One of my favorites at Red Wing.  Its' the longest route on Barn Bluff.  Once you get past the first 20ft of lie back flake its smooth sailing on big jugs.

name: Micro Balls
description: Another one of my favorite routes at Red Wing.  Climb the dihedral and move to the left a bit following the bolts.  If you can not see the next bolt, do not despair it is hidden over a small overhang.  Not as polished as many of the routes in this area.   RCM&W, #63, p.130.

name: Out Of Control
description: The route is the middle line from the start of Geriatrics, etc.  It's about 25 feet to the left of Annadonia.  I really liked this route.  It's much less sandy than Geriatrics.     RCM&W #71, p. 130

name: Quiet Desperation
description: Quiet Desperation climbs a faint arete located thirty feet to the right of Femme Fatale and twenty feet to the left of Stylin/Out of Control/Geriatric Sex Maniacs from Mars.    Quiet is, ahem, a desperate, little bugger. The route gets going on the first move, a big throw off a good right hand crimp and an ok left hang crimp/pinch to either a two-finger pocket or a crimp. This move is easier for tall folks. From the pocket, a tenuous move deposits the climber at a rest on a nice edge. Getting to the next rest, two huecos, requires lots of tension and precision. This is the physical crux of the route. After resting at the huecos, tricky moves lead to the last bolt, which is a little farther away than most would like. This is the redpoint/mental crux. From the last bolt, it's Red Wing sand jugs to the top. With desperate moves down though and some tenuous cruxing up high, crisp temps are extremely helpful for sending this rig.

name: Rock-a-holics
description: Not for the faint at heart.  The crux is committing to start the route.  If you don't mind the runout 1st and 2nd bolts, this climb is FUN.  This route meanders left and right of the bolts.     RCM&W #59, p. 126

name: Rude Awakening
