After traversing all the way out to the prow, topout straight up the prow with a high foot and a big move to a positive crimper (crux) and then top-out carefully.  This is an excellent boulder problem.

name: The Reverse Traverse
description: This route traverses the entirety of the cliff from the left. It has a totally different feel than the pump traverse as you hook and toe your way around the prow. This route is very fun and recommended.

name: Zot
description: The route comes straight out the overhang and then up the face on the East (right) side of the boulder. Use a spotter because one crux is late in the game. Probably Mankato's best boulder problem.

name: Alma Mater
description: This route moves up the obvious weakness in the middle of the roof.  Start out on good holds which quickly turn to ridiculously good holds.  Climb up through the roof and keep your head cool as you top out.    A very fun climb up steep terrain!    This route is nasty when the area is wet, so do it when it's dry.

name: Crank Artist of the Prairie
description: Start just right (or on) Alma Mater and follow good holds up and then almost immediately right, traversing straight across the lip of the overhang, hooking and toeing feet as you fight the pump and move all the way across the boulder on good holds.  Top out in easy terrain just right of a large scary block (which you climb below and DONT PULL ON).  This is one of Mankato's better boulder problems.    May need a little cleaning depending on the season, so bring your brush!

name: The Bulge
description: Start on a decent left hand sidepull/pinch with right hand lower on a undercling/sidepull.  Make a big move up to the right arete (or small moves on VERY small holds).  Then climb straight up the arete to the top.

name: Far Right Overhang
description: Start on the obvious huge side-pull, pull through the short overhang and then up the slab.

name: Finger Crackin
description: The only sit start problem at the Boulder due to its height. Climb the finger crack straight up using jams.

name: Left Slab
description: Bring a brush and maybe you'll find more holds!  Thin moves up a slabby face.

name: Lefter Slab
description: Head straight up the side of the boulder with a good left hand side pull and right hand pinch. Consistently good left hands, consistently mediocre right hands.

name: Leftest Slab
description: Grab the obvious jugs and go

name: The Lizard King's Traverse
description: Same start as the Lonliest Climber in Mankato, and traverse all the way left. There is a large reddish brown spot on the far left side of the rock. As soon as the spot is directly to your left, make your way up to the top of the boulder. It is bunch of small crimps the whole way over and up

name: The Loneliest Climber in Mankato
description: Head up the tallest part of the boulder on the flat face.  Great problem.

name: The Rat King’s Traverse
description: Start on the start holds to White Trash Beach Bash, and traverse left through Thundercling to Right Overhang, and top out.

name: The Rat Kong’s Traverse
description: Start on the start holds of White Trash Beach Bash (left hand sloper, right hand undercling) and traverse through Thundercling to Right Overhang, then top out.

name: Thundercling
description: This route climbs right to left and basically ends with the same top-out as 'Far-Right Overhang.'     Work left using the underclings and holds on the overhang, staying low.  Work your way to the start of the bulge and top-out right.    Continuing the traverse left across the bulge and topping out on Loneliest Climber likely adds a grade or two.

name: White Trash Beach Bash
description: Start with right hand on the undercling, left hand on the terrible sloper. Use the obvious left foot to pull your body onto the slab and use the sharp crimps to beached whale the rest of your body onto the slab.

name: Anything But
description: Start on the face and traverse left, then follow the nose all the way up.

name: Cover Shot
description: 2 variations:   Big moves up the right arete, topping out straight up (recommended).   Or easier climbing up the left arete through worse rock.    The crux of this route is the head game.

name: Depth Perception
description: Follow the crack all the way up using only the crack. Fist jams with a few hand jambs. V1 if you end up using the holds to the sides of the crack.

name: Peter's Dihedral
description: Hand jambs, finger jambs, layback flakes, drop knees, heel hooks, dynos... you can utilize any combination of these unnecessary moves to send Peter's Dihedral.      Necessity is the mother of invention, it is true -- but it's father is creativity.   - Jonathan Schattke

name: Toad
description: One of the better routes in the Rasmussen West area.  Find the crimper and sloper/crimper on the lip of the roof.  4 or 5 fun moves, then you're done :)

name: Unknown 1
description: Climber's leftmost route of the main wall at Memorial Park, this route starts with a few crimps, moves to a jug shelf, and finishes just over a horizontal seam. Currently, the anchors have two auto-locking biners that make clipping a bit difficult to manage one handed. Bring two draws for the anchors if anyone is coming up behind you or if you are not confident you can hang out and monkey with the biners currently there.    (If this is your route and you want edits made, contact me and I will oblige.)

name: Unknown 2
description: Mixed climb or highball to first bolt.  Start in crack right of anchors, work up using crack and face holds. Move left to first bolt (~20' off deck) and progress to anchors.    (If this is your route and you want edits made, contact me and I will oblige.)

name: Unnamed Arete
description: Arete leading to shared anchors.  Start on right side of face and use crimps and shelves on and around arete to move up and left.  Crux is using a small left hand crimp to gain a nice right hand side pull around the third bolt.  Continue moving left to shared anchor.    Currently, the anchors have two auto-locking biners that make clipping a bit difficult to manage one handed. Bring two draws for the anchors if anyone is coming up behind you or if you are not confident you can hang out and monkey with the biners currently there.

name: Unnamed Face
description: Start left, start right, start up the middle, but whatever you do... start this route!  Climbed from the right side for the lead FA, this route offers nice crimps, feet, and a small roof for your climbing pleasure.  The first bolt can be reached from the horizontal crack below the roof and then it is game on.  For full value, stay straight up the face.  However, there is a bulge to the left of the bolt line that can be employed to avoid the crimpy crux.  Short, but sweet.

name: The Beginners 's Crack
description: Easy crack climb.. as long as your here you might as well wander up it.

name: Black Ice
description: Steep wall that looks to seep water a bit...  Looks like good crimps to some big reaches at top.

name: Brodizaffa
description: The arete and flake to the left of 6-foot flake.

name: The Front Page
description: 3 Bolt slab route.  Flat landing so bouldering it is  all good if you are OK with a little highball action.

name: Kris can do it
description: Bolted route just to the left of Quagmire. Up a zig-zagging thin crack with positive, but thin, side-pulls. Continuously 5.10 to the top without any terrific rests.    I personally enjoyed this route quite a bit. Worth doing a few laps on for a workout.

name: Liv's Traverse
description: A very fun line! Climb up to the slab to the right of the obvious horizontal crack. There is no protection until you reach the crack. Traverse the crack with solid hands and poor feet until the crack diminishes. From there, follow up the right facing dihedral to the top. Use the tree as an anchor to belay up a second.

name: Moss chaos
description: Starts two hand on the chalky side pull. Bump your left hand up to the small crack/crimp just above the start hold. Dino to the sloper about 4 feet (rough estimate)above and to the right of the start hold and then top out of the route! Solid route for anyone who likes pumpy slab routes![[]]

name: The Parachute Club
description: One of the longest routes at the quarry. Starts in a left-facing dihedral on the broken corner to the left and down the wall from quagmire. If this location description is confusing, then just look for the only route with 4 bolts up it (although the 4th bolt is useless, and probably for the 5.13 on the face just to the right of this climb). The crux of the route is about 5-feet off the ground, where some stemming will make up for less-than-ideal hands. Past the crux is easier ground to the top.

name: Quagmire
description: Wet corner with what must be an appropriate name.

name: Six Foot Flake
description: 3 bolts, start on crack/flake at the left side of the slab.  Follow bolts.

name: Stepping Stones
description: Very easy route, good for beginners.

name: Sucker Punch
description: Fun Route, watch out for the ledges!

name: Lost
description: Head straight up from a obvious triangle start hold on the steep. Mantel is a bit committing  and powerful. Take your time on the upper slab.

name: Lost sit
description: Sit start on 2 obvious crimps, move up and right to the start of Lost. Long moves and a intermediate crimp will get you to the stand start. Head straight up.

name: 01) Hot German Babe
description: "Follow arete on left side of Diagonals Wall. Tricky but easy 5.8 with one move 5.10. Learn how to mantle, think left palm. Start on Diagonals Wall and lieback right on the flake on the drill holes.   WARNING: Do not start climb around corner to left next to tree. This is loose death block and your could bring down multiple blocks. We marked it with X's"    Named for my hot german girlfriend Gaby    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 02) Nick The Wonder Dog
description: Work the first set of 3 drill holes on left side of diagonals wall. Pretty hard to link moves together. One move 5.11/12 move depending on height, then a couple 5.11's and the rest is easy.    UPDATE: 10/22/15: Crux hold broke off this year. Not sure what the rating is but probably in 12 range. I added bolt to crux.    Named after Joe's awesome German Shephard crag dog. Calm, didn't bug other climbers, didn't bark, didn't eat other people's food, didn't bark at other dogs, didn't hunt and kill wildlife. Joe could just look at him and Nick would just know what to do, like move to avoid a falling rope. That dog read a climbers mind. Miss him.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 02.5) Bolts Over Troubled Water
description: 3rd route right from the left arete.

name: 03) Ramp Of Death
description: SPORTY!!!!! but very very cool ramp. Stay on the ramp to be pure, don't wus out and go to side ledges and climb up.      This used to be a bit runout, but by popular demand I bolt-protected the cruxes. 8 bolts total. So maybe I should call it "Ramp Of Pain" now. I think this is one of the best 5.9's in the state.    This route reminds me a bit of Drilling Experience in Red Wing but a lot longer on the slab.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 04) Barron  Von  Mischke
description: Same start as Ramp of Death but finish straight up. The cool crux is at the last 15 feet. Work the drill holes to the right of the bolts. There are lips on them that you lie back. If you can get your foot in the little slot in the drill hole and then big throw to ledge on left left of bolt. You can also go up left on ledges but the lie back is way too cool. Finish on tiny ledges to the right of the anchor.  Mostly 5.8 moves until the top panel. You can escape right if you can't do it.    Try to avoid the inscription on the wall from 1915. It is historical value.    Named after Joe's latest crag dog in training.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 05) Bolt Bolt Boltin on Heaven's Door.
description: Same start as Ramp of Death, go up until wall turns blank at big ledge. Head right on big ledge to a single bolt until standing under double bolt holes. 5.10 if you go over the small roof, but route is meant to escape right 5.8 onto the ramp.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 05.5) Bolters on the Storm
description: Up 2 bolts and left about 2 feet. Then up to small overhang. Last 2 moves are crux. Last 2 moves go left over the small overhang (don't wuss out on the right ramp), think about your where to put your hands before you move.    Bolted 8/18/15: Gaby Brausam and Michael Endrizzi    Gaby and I use to sing this classic Doors song in the car.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 06) FBBMEAJMFFAMEUFA
description: Easy ramp. Look out for falling on iron bars, we tried to bolt so you wouldn't hit them. I even put in another bolt after the fact to doubly protect it. Could be a ball sack ripper if your a guy, not sure what to say for the ladies. Angle up the diagonal left.    If you belayer is a skinny 90 pound when wet, you might want to tie them in or they will go for a huge swing on free top-rope.    Name dedicated to a climber that was trying to describe how to 'properly' label first ascents on lead, but on something that was top-roped previously. FA or FFA or FFFFFA or FBABCXYZ or WTF?    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 06.5) Kletterfreude
description: 5.10 for short people, 5.9 for tall.    Follow the boltline. 2 cruxes, middle and top. At the top go straight up below the anchors along the drill holes and finish at top ledge. No cheating off on the left ramp.    Bolted 8/25/15 Gaby Brausam and Mike Endrizzi    German for "the enjoyment of climbing."    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 07) Dirty bolts and their done dirt cheap
description: Start on left arcing ramp using undercling but head straight up. Has cool finish on finger ledges below the anchors.    This was original route on wall with top anchors but can't figure out who put them there.     Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 08) Supercalifragalisticexpi-BOLT-adocious
description: Hard start but pretty cool finish on drill hole edges. First two panels stay left of bolts. Carefull over the spikes, I tried to bolt protect them. Last panel is the best climbing on drill hole edges layback to left.Stay totally on face all the way up to anchors - don't go right at the end that is tooooo easy. 5.10 start with rest 5.8. Maybe a little harder at end if you stay on panel.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 09) Boltway to Heaven
description: 5.10 start on small crimpers to first ledge. Easy moves to top ledge. Cool crack finish, total use of cranking right hand ring lock and must trust feet.Status: Still dirty haven't cleaned foilage yet 9/23/09  Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 10) Cavedago - Gateway To Spormaggiorre
description: Diagonal ramp. Start is crux then easy until left side of 3rd shelf. Easiest and safest if you head all the way left to parallel next bolt and then straight up. If you decide to head up diagonally then its 5.10b or so because no feet and small crack will kill your fingers. Getting to the next bolt is a bit thrilling because you are off balance, but protected by bolt at your knees so should be safe.    I overbolted with 9 bolts so aspiring 5.8 climbers could practice leading on not worry about shelves.    My mom lived in Spor Italy and my dad lived in Cavedago the sister town. They use to fight over what town was best. They are the gateway to the Dolomites - most beautiful mountains in the world.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 11) Packen Wir Es An!!!!
description: Start 2 feet right of Cavedago, but do not use those holds. Head straight up. Hard start on little crimpers. Use undercling left and right (hidden). Lie back right for the first 7 feet. After first move then use holds on left and lie back right.    Final panel is pretty cool too. Little crimpers. Make sure you finish all the way to the top.    Gaby named it. In English "Let's Do It!!!"    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 11.5 Purple Bolt, Purple Bolt
description: Cool climb. 1st panel pull up no feet. 2nd panel crux in middle. Batman. 3rd panel PALM mantel PALM mantel PALM mantel. Avoid questionable rocks at the top, marked with X.    Bolted by Michael Endrizzi May 2016    Not a big Prince fan, but lots of people liked him. Apollonia was hot.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 12) Quantum Chaos
description: Start in right corner below dead tree. Easy moves to middle of climb below roof. Veer left and use left edges and drill hole to approach roof. Mini-crux is pulling the mini-roof. Dicier crux is then to try and stand up on the slab to get to the anchors. Do NOT!!! touch the crack to the right at any time!!!! Trust the feet. Stay on slab.    Named by physists Chuck Wilcox.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 13) Quantum Order
description: Easy movement along crack to the right of quantum chaos.  Only interesting movement was a high foot-jam to pull the roof at the crux.     Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: Community Service
description: A bit of a crux getting to the first bolt, but then fun after that.  Stem up the blank section till you can get the jug on the right.  Then reach back left and go straight up.  It's a bit run out to the chains, but on pretty easy climbing.  If you got to the first bolt, this should not be a problem    This route can be rock climbed or drytooled.    Equiped by Jeff Engel, not sure who got the FA, although it has been drytooled before I am sure

name: Derailed
description: This climbs starts just around the corner from  Spray on the Main Flow Wall.  It’s the only bolted line currently on the wall.  Start up the easy arete for the first two bolts, then battle the crux by traversing right along on thin rail of crimps and bad feet that get increasingly better.  After the 3 bolt, follow the bolt line straight up the  face, leading to a small roof and the wild red-point crux!  Once you stick the jug, you have the option to clip the last bolt of Spray on the arete or climb up a few more feet and clipping the last bolt of Derailed. Complete the final few moves to the shared anchor and Bobs your uncle.

name: Dimples
description: Using the drill hole and large dimples for your feet reach high and clip the first bolt.  Climb up to the seemingly blank face to find a nice crimp, step up and gaston the flake on the right to get a jug.  Continue up moderate climbing to the top.    This is a fun rock route, but can be drytooled also.  Please becareful drytooling to not destroy too many holds

name: Mad Dogs
description: A bit of a trusty move on a side pull and a sloper foot to get to the first bolt.  The middle is fun with side pulls and gastons.  Crux is just before the last ledge.  There is a bit of fun between the last bolt and the anchors though.    This route can be rock climbed or drytooled. The top is currently kindof dirty and harder than it should be because of that.  I will clean it the next time I am there.    I named it Mad Dogs because the day I redpointed it my dog Pele was attacked by another dog.  Usually Pele is very submissive and just wants to have lots of friends.  I was pretty pissed at the owner of this dog and the dog at first.  Eventually the owner came over to apologize.  Apparently this puppy use to be a very social dog - until it got hit by a train and almost died.  I guess shit happens to dogs that make them hard and cold too.    There is one set of top anchors on the left of this route.  It can be toproped and I equip it next summer.

name: Spray
description: clip the first bolt and dive into the crux.  Use the small side pull and reach high to a small crimp just to the left of the second bolt.  Step up and grab the half drill hole and figure out how to mantle on top of the slopey corner.  follow the arete to the top    There are some indication this route was drytooled at some point.  It is a very fun rock climbing route and it would be a shame if it was damaged from drytooling.  This is the only route I would like to see not drytooled anymore.

name: Adoption
description: (Equipped by J. Engel and M. Endrizzi) 15 feet left of "Compromises". This is an excellent route with the 2 cruxes: one at the very start and one at the very end. Crank up on small but good in-cuts to do a hand & foot match (yoga practitioners will find this easier than most). Climb vertical rail feature to a whitish, slightly mungy section about halfway up. Move left and then up through large horizontal cracks to upper headwall. Hopefully, you've saved a little juice to pull through the last move crux using the pods and slots that take you to the top.

name: Adoptomises
description: I thought I'd add this in hopes more people do this very fun link up. It starts on compromises and traverses over to adoption after the 4th bolt. There is a bolt protecting the traverse. You get the hard parts of both routes with a little less pump than adoption and a little more cruxin' than compromises.   Also, the best warm up you have ever had is doing compromises, the linkup, and adoption in rapid succession.   Any knowledge of the actual name, FA or equipper would be appreciated.

name: Arbor Day
description: Same start as Adoption but veer right near top.

name: Compromises
description: Left-most route on Realtionship Wall.  Slighlty loose flake to face and pockets above.  Consistently fun moves throughout.

name: Harvest Moon
description: This short but stellar rig tackles the center of the "booty wall", equipped by Jeff Engel, Tyler Hoffart and their wonderful group of volunteers for the 2013 Save Sandstone Festival. Start on crimper sequences to the second bolt and move to the amazing, obvious arched slopper. Get tricky with your feet and figure out how not to peel off. The crux is short lived - easier yet engaging climbing will bring you to the chains.

name: KYG
description: Getting off the ground is interesting. Rest of the route is moderate. Good fun warm up. Go WAY left to make it easy, or veer right to get full value.  When we cleaned off the bottom part of the climb we found some graffiti on the wall. Go climb it and see what it says :)  Equipped by Jeff Engel.  Send it in the dark. If you're going to TR - follow / unclip as it wanders.

name: Stage Fright
description: Another line born from the Save Sandstone Festival. A burly undercling crux starts the route, followed by a crimper traverse and gaston sequences. Although relatively short, this techy climb packs a punch on some pretty cool sequences. If only it could continue for longer.

name: Start New
description: Gain a vegetated ledge 2/3rds the way up, then fire off into some sweet face and arete moves. Super fun movement.     The crux is high on the arete. The line takes you on an adventure!    The lower part requires a bit of balance.    Equipped by Jeff Engel.

name: Buckthorn Brawler
description: Sit-start on obvious right hand edge and good left sloper. Pull a tough move straight up and head left for the lip. Pull the lip and keep your feel on!

name: The End Of The Beginning
description: Sit-Start crossed on left hand sloper, Right hand pinch-crimp. pull up to lip and traverse to the 2/3rds mark. Pull the lip and hope your feet stay on!

name: Honeysuckle Heavy
description: Sit-start low on good right edge and good left sloper. Make a tough move straight up. Head right for the slopey arete and round it out.

name: Jason Patrock
description: Arete left of Quarry Feldman.  Sit start, up to right, then follow side pull rail on left to top.

name: Kiefer Sitterland
description: Start low on Quarry Feldman, sitting on the big rock at the base of the boulder.

name: License to Drive
description: Stand start. Warm up line. Or, dyno from lower holds to lip!

name: Poached Ivory
description: Fun little route we found just off the side of the road before crossing the bridge to eldon. Start matches on a jug a move out right to gain a big rail. Work up the rail to a nice slot. Work up the two offset jugs to the top out.

name: Quarry Feldman
description: Stand start, up and right.

name: Quarry Haim
description: Stand start on obvious jug, up and left.

name: Free Apples
description: Slabby warm up. Crux is getting established. Right foot dimple, right hand side pull, how will you get started? From there, friction is your friend for a couple moves and then, holds abound.

name: Number Lover
description: Sit start with good right hand pocket.  Moves up and left.  Finished using crack system on left side of arete.  Probably a direct finish for a harder grade - top out was still damp after cleaning, so didn't attempt.

name: Number Lover Direct
description: Start as Number Lover, but do not move left around boulder. Go straight up for mantle finish.

name: Tenth Wife
description: Start on good right hold, left crimp, and foot under roof. Traverse left to arete, then up. May or may not involve cutting feet depending on your technique/beta.

name: Passiveschist
description: Sit start low left, work up rail to right, find sloper over lip, work feet up, and continue up face to top. Easy exit on back side of boulder.

name: unknown
description: Lynn Larson cleaned this boulder for the 2013 Save Sandstone Festival. Then, it snowed and she never climbed it. In 2014, it has obviously been climbed. By whom? I don't know. If you want to claim an FA or throw out a name, contact me.    This problem has been wet on dry days, so be aware before climbing it. Don't climb wet sandstone. Took a guess at the rating too. Posting it now only to make it available. I will revamp this page when I know more about it.

name: 0.1) Do You Think I'm Saxy?
description: Very left of Sax Wall. Well bolted 5.8 meant for aspiring leaders.    Start in corner. Clip first bolt a little high. Easy to next bolt and begin crux. Look out for  sloper! Try to head for drill hole on right, use your feet in big crack.    If you make the crux its easiest if you swing over right. But more cool if you go straight up over the overhang.    Rest is easy, last move to bolts is a little hard but on huge huge holds. Pull ups work.    Bolted by dreez: 5/14/2012    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 1) A Little Spicy!!!
description: Start left of bolt. Use foot ledges on left and lie back on good drill hole edges up high left and right.    Was named because it gets "spicy" above last bolt but I went back and bolt protected it. Joe said this is a sax solo for some punk band.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 2) Body and Soul
description: Start left of bolt, crimpy undercling. Hard move with hole in it, then head straight up. At first ledge go right a little, then angle back left lying back left. Follow ledges up climbing thru the bolts.    Named by a great sax man Pat Makin for John Coltrane and best sax ballad ever written.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 3) Morphine
description: Start below bolt and go over bolt and straight up using small hand holds above bolt.  From first ledge go straight up over bolts.    When get to cave, use left side of cave only, stay to immediate right of bolts.  Climb over the bolts at the end, can use arete.     Named for a band called Morphine with a great sax section    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 4) Sax-a-holic
description: From the start below drill hole go right over drill hole. From the second ledge, go straight over the first two bolts, at second bolt there is secret move and go straight up through the bolts to huge hand hold. Right over the bolts using tiny finger ledges, to bigger finger ledges. Head right after last bolt.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 5) Multiple SAX Partners
description: "   For start, right of bolt in the angling right crack.From the first ledge go up to immedge right of bolts to finger ledges.From second  ledge, go up finger holds up the panels and use finger holds on right and left of panel, and then do layback at top. Clipping the bolt is a bit of a stretch but can be done if you get your feet high enough. Use long draw too. Last panel, go up same panel where bolt is, can't use holds on left or right. Tall man reach to get to hand ledge. Above the bolt go straight up the final panel, use half moon tiny old, very slopy, use drill holes for feet."  Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 6) No such THANG as Too Much Sax
description: "   Starts right below the bolts. From the first ledge  go up left of bolts until you get to drill hole. At drill hole, cross right and climb body over the bolt. Then go up two thin finger ledges above bolt. Can also layback on drill holes. Last panel, clip the bolt and stay on the left 3'. Last move is hard on fingery holds, can use all shelves from bolted panel and panel on left.   "   Dry toolers stay off this route or the top, you are ruining the last moves.    Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: 7) Crack With No Name
description: Trad climb crack that starts on far right and traverses left to middle of wall. Excellent trad crack that sucks gear. Great holds and feet. Some overhangs with big holds. Finish at birch tree in middle of wall.  Prefer no drytooling here. Drytooling destroys routes. Tradition is to use web anchors and trad gear   if you really need to drytool. Bolts are for sport climbers. Let's save these climbs for YOUR kids. Thanks. Dreez

name: Nakoma (formerly The Niche)
description: 30 feet right of Wild Things.    Stick clip first two bolts, as the first 10-12 moves compose a hard boulder poem that leaves no room for clipping nor tea. TECHNERFUL (Technical AND Powerful)   A unique and thrilling traverse section, tricky clip and dihedral prayer will show you to an enjoyable and victorious second-half of rock climbing.     Previously, this line of rock was known as The Niche, a 12b top rope that started on Wild Things and traversed 30ish feet into a 5.12 face/arete/dihedral. In early spring of 2013, a more direct and difficult start was identified and bolted. This, along with the removal of two very large, loose and dangerous blocks from the dihedral, transformed the line into a much different and difficult sport route.   The Niche was first climbed, on top rope, by Mike Dahlberg circa 1988.

name: Nexus
description: This route was finally bolted for sport in Sept 2011 (with permission from Mike Dahlberg).  HYPER CLASSIC.   Route immediately left of Sigma.   Stick clip first bolt or climb good holds to first.   Has a little bit of everything; liebacking, stemming, pinching, crimping, jamming, pocket-filling and a redpoint crux guarding the anchors. A very special line.     Hard to believe that two routes of this caliber exist right beside each other in Minnesota. Believe it.    This, along with all five routes in this area, were first climbed by Dahlberg circa 1988.   First Lead Ascent by Sean Ferrell.

name: Sigma
description: A pumpy route. Have the belayer be watchful for the 3rd clip. Clean line with good moves. There are a couple of spots with a bit of crumbly rock.   Not so much of a distinct crux, linking together is the key, IMO.

name: Tool Boy
description: Up flakes on Wild Things (don't trust flake for pro) to a stance on horizontal ledge leading to right.  Walk on air across traverse to stance below roof and in corner.  Up to roof then out right to hidden, hanging off hands crack to anchors right of final outside corner.

name: Wild Things
description: Route immediatley right of Sigma.  Follow right facing accute corner to roof.  Pull through inobvious moves to somewhat runout section to top.  Anchors on left wall or top out.  Solid 9-10 trad-leaders will enjoy this--others may not.

name: All Along the Watertower
description: Sit start low right on good hold where roof begins, traverse left over roof, then up to ledge for top out. Can walk off ledge to the right or continue up and over upper face.    Found in Fall 2013, cleaned holds and relocated a large carpet of moss on ledge. Assuming FA was mine, but you never know at this area. Lots of pioneers before me and nothing documented. Correct me if I'm wrong and I'll gladly update.    Don't climb wet rock.

name: All for V4
description: Best V5's younger bro.  Classy sandstone jugs the whole way.  Crux is the intro moves.  Enjoy.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: All for V6
description: All for V4 low start. Climb through pocket underclings on the roof and into big sloper pinches on the face. Head left and finish out on All for V4.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.    -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.    -Leave no trace. Erase tick marks. Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: The Alternator
description: Fun, albeit sharp moderate. Start on incut rails to the right of the base of the arete.  Climb the good, sharp incuts to the top.

name: Best Boulder in Minnesota
description: Deserved of the name.  Fun gymnastic climbing to a long lock-off crux to an exciting top out.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Best Touch
description: Climb Invisible Touch (V8) to the arete, then drop down and make hard moves to reach the start of Best V5.  Drop down nature of the climb is why I give it 4 stars.  That said, I have not climbed it.  So I am just a lazy hack!    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: The Bow Hunter
description: Once upon a time in 2012, I was visiting Sandstone for my second or third time with two buddies.  One of them had never been there, the other had been a few times with climbers who regularly went there.  The latter gentleman was driving.  He parked in front of the locked gate at the end of the dirt road that now, in 2014, is open to the climbing community.  At the time, this was still private land.    We hiked down to the boulders, spent the day climbing, and returned to his car to find a massive truck parked inches from his bumper.  We were blocked in.  We called out for a while and several minutes later, a man in camouflage and blaze orange approached us from the woods.  He carried in his hand, a bow.    The hunter was not happy that we were there and proceeded to tell us that he had permission from the land owners to hunt there and that we were not allowed.  We explained that it was our understanding that climbers had verbal permission from the owner to be there, but if we were wrong about that, we would not return.  In this conversation, the hunter said the land was for sale and that he would buy it and not allow climbers to return.    He drove off and we made our way back down the road worried about what had just happened.  I reached out to the MCA about the situation and a series of events was set into motion.  In 2013, the climbing community banded together, worked with the non-profit Parks & Trails Council of MN, and helped PTCM purchase the land preserving climbers access.    If we had not run into that hunter that day, if he had not been so angry and threatened us with the idea of purchasing the land for himself, what a different story it might have been.    In the fall of 2013, I began exploring Eldon on my own looking for things that seemed unclimbed.  This problem was my first attempt at developing something in this area.    In honor of that man, it is named The Bow Hunter.    Sit start on crimps below the roof, work up to the base of the left side of the roof, use crimps to work out to the nose, then mount that sucker.  Good luck and watch your landing.

name: Carburetor
description: Easy problem around the left corner from The Alternator. Start on the left side and follow a diagonal crack up and right to the topout.

name: Chairman Meow
description: Dabby start, rad couple of moves.  Sit-start to the right of the arete on decent holds.  Make a difficult moves to the arete and an even more difficult move to stand up.  Easy top-out.

name: Contortion
description: Start in the hole on two mini jugs, go out the cave and to the lip to an easy mantle.

name: The Cutting Edge AKA Pocket Hercules Left
description: Start as for Pocket Hercules, traverse left and gain the sharp slot before heading to the lip and pressing it out.

name: First Born Traverse
description: Dabby moves, rad slopers.  Start on massive detached flake.  Make big move to the lip, then traverse right, all the way to the end.  Crux is in the middle.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.    -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.    -Leave no trace. Erase tick marks. Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Helke V3
description: Start on jug rail and move straight up, finishing with an exciting rail.  Rock quality down low is only reason for not giving 4 stars.  Very fun mantle problem.

name: Invisible Touch
description: Quality.  Only negative is that for this problem to be climbed the river must be either frozen or at very low water.  Start on flat jug.  Move through a pinch and then ride the crimps on the arete.  Finish with tough moves on slopers.      REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Last Touch
description: Start on the new school start of best V5 (left hand mini pinch right hand sloper jug) and trav right into the finishing sloper of invisible touch. shmantle. needs another ascent.     water usually sits under the landing making the line somewhat sketchy at times.    want to hear what others think of it. unsure of grade...

name: Lean With It, Rock With It
description: Start on Tengo De La Muerte (V10), finish on the slab to the right. Tengo begins in the hole, below the boulder.  You begin on rounded crimps.  Get to the mini-jug, move to the slab (crux), execute the techy top out.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.    -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.    -Leave no trace. Erase tick marks. Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: The Nervous Addition
description: Fun feature climbing. Start on mini-horn feature that has a crimp on either side.  Make moderate moves to the arete, then devise a solution to get to the stand start jug start hold.  At least two ways of getting this done.  Finish on Panic Arete Stand.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: The Nose Thing
description: Fun climbing, but a bit of an eliminate.  Start on the pedestal below the boulder.  Climb the arete feature.  Do not use the holds to the right.     This has been climbed as an off-width by some masochistic individuals.      REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Nutrigrain (a.k.a. Please Hammer Don't Hurt Em')
description: Cool hards, with an optional drop-knee in a V5: Count me in!  Sit-start, get to jugs at half-way height, finish big.      REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: On Ice
description: Start with your hands on the crack, end on top of the rock.   Let me know if this route has previously been named.

name: Panic Arete Stand
description: Start with right hand in jug on face and left hand on arete.  Climb the arete.  Keep it together on the top out.  Scope the top out -- and brush it of leaves and what not -- before climbing.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Pocket Hercules
description: Burly classic.  Start on fragile pinch/crimp jug, then make long moves to good holds.  Mantle the top.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: R-Naught
description: Sit start and move up and right. Top out on shelf. Walk/Honnold off shelf to climber's right. Spotters recommended more for getting off the shelf than for getting up. Fun, big moves on mediocre rock. Feel free to modify the name/grade if this is in the Helke guide.

name: The Raven Stand
description: Stand start on crimp rails, climb more crimps to the top.  Very quality stone.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: The Raven
description: Long term project put to rest by Nik O.  He earned this one.  Only seen a few repeats, including ascents by Daniel Woods and Paul Robinson.  Both said they found the problem to be of high quality.    Sit-start in obvious pocket jug.  Move up the feature, finishing to the left on crimps.  Paul finished straight up.  Crux is the intro moves.  Note: I have not climbed this.  Just rated it to give users an idea of the quality.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Riverside Direct
description: Start on shelf/crack under roof. Jam and reach out to mini pinch on face. Work face up to the perfect loaf pinch on V4. Top out straight up over jagged jug or use right OG exit in winter.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.    -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.    -Leave no trace. Erase tick marks. Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Riverside Jump or Swim
description: Start hands matched on lone flat edge in the middle of the face. Find some feet and jump to the dark water stained jug at the lip.    Sketchy but doable in the summer. Just have a spotter for your spotter so everyone doesn't go tumbling into the river.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.    -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.    -Leave no trace. Erase tick marks. Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Riverside V4
description: Classic.  Given three stars for dabby start.  Start on jugs.  Traverse right on slopers.  Once at the face, climb nice sandstone mini-jugs to the lip.  Tricky mantel to finish.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Rock Wid It
description: Start on the prominent rail, climb the slab. A cool mono crimp-dish and a committing move guard the top out mantle.

name: Tengo De La Muerte
description: Compression power enduro block.  Start right hand on crimp, left hand on the blocky feature farther down.  Get to the mini-jug at the base of the arete, then compress to the top.  Stand start (aka where the compression begins) is V6/7.     REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: That Girl's a Bitch
description: One of the, if not the, best slab problems in MN.    REMEMBER:    -If it has rained in the past 24 hours, do not climb at Eldon.   -Wipe your shoes off before you climb.   -Leave no trace.  Erase tick marks.  Pack out any trash, yours or others'.

name: Warmup Wall
description: Many variations on the same boulder. A short problem with hundreds of hold options.

name: 10,000 Teeth
description: Sit start low and slap your way along the sloping lip. Bear hug and burl your way until you reach the peak. Top out right.

name: Absolution
description: Highball on a vertical face. Starts in a crack on the left then cuts back right halfway up following the seams. Be ready to gun for the top!

name: The Amateur
description: This is only the stand start to the once deemed 'impossible' 50 degree wall. Jim Merli's "L' Etoilie du Nord" (Amateur SDS) is Minnesota's (and probably the Midwest's) hardest problem. The stand begins in the middle of the rail and is only a few moves long...hard moves and sharp.

name: Andy's Arete
description: Best problem on the Dragon Head boulder, and a very attractive feature with a lot of good holds. It really borders on V3, and a lot of people find it a tad easier than The Prow V3.

name: Andy's Dyno
description: Another problem in the warm-up circuit.  Start with hands matched on the arete and feet matched on large flat foothold that forms the base of the boulder. Move up to the break, then paste your feet and dyno/deadpoint straight up to the next break and top out. Be careful on the top out. To descend, walk towards the Juggernaut boulder.

name: Andy's Problem
description: Start on to holds move into a crimp then do a huge lock off and lunge to arete.     this description could be off, if anyone heads up there take a look at it.

name: Back side of Lushes Lip
description: Sit Start at the right corner. Use arete to pull up, and move out left or keep going up right arete. Either way is pretty easy but following the right arete requires more precise footwork and is more fun. An ok warm up and good for beginners.

name: Back Slapper
description: Because this problem is wedged between two boulders, it takes away from it's quality. Otherwise a good problem that is only 3 hand moves.

name: Back Slapper Traverse
description: Same weird start as 'Back Slapper', but follow the rail left and up.

name: Backpay
description: Short, powerful problem. Start on obvious undercling flake. Make a big move out right and finish straight up to the peak of the boulder.

name: beefstick buffet
description: Crux is the top out, Start with feet on huge shelf. Hands on holds just short of waist level, up to slopey side pull and up to the top out.

name: Betty's Pie
description: A really fun climb with some cool moves. start on the left side of face, work up arrete on crimps until you have to roll through right into the sloping top out. A lower start is probably possible.

name: The Budda Boulder
description: This boulder has a couple possible lines.  One starting underneath & moving left over a glued hold.  One moving right & up onto the overhanging arete.  The arete alone was supposedly climbed by Matt Tschol.  The slab to the right of the main over hanging face was first climbed by Kris Johnson.

name: Bulldozer
description: Sit start, then work up the right side of this face while doing a couple of cool dynos. The arete to the right is off.

name: Censored
description: A very nice and tricky slab boulder that is much more technical than it may appear at first glance.  Stand start on a crimp rail, and climb the slab.

name: Counselor Moon
description: One of the best V7's in Minnesota, and unique for Sawmill. This problem is a stand start on the slot jug, then immediately goes onto the 45 overhang. With these nice skin-friendly holds, work your way up the center of the face towards the dihedral. Prepare for a cool but scary finish move. Be careful of the huge opening to your right.

name: Easy Crack
description: SDS and climb up through steep break in rock.  Top-out right.

name: Enter the Dragon
description: This problem is located on the Dragon Head Boulder (see location info below).  The problem involves an ugly beached whale mantel.  This movement reminds me of humping, hence the name, Enter the Dragon.  Clever!  Nod your head.     Enter the Dragon begins on the side of the boulder closest to Jaws and Nic-o-rete. Begin with a low, awkard start, make a couple easy moves to the lip, then get your hump on.

name: The Exodus
description: One of the few proud lines in Minnesota. This technical and powerful traverse doesn't have any moves harder than V8, but it builds up after about 20'. The first third is a great warm up, then it gets serious with a deadpoint redpoint crux to a mean hold. Followed by a unique top out. Very fun!

name: Ezekiel's Prophecy
description: SDS on the left side of the arete, move around to the right and climb pockets and chickenheads up the face.

name: Footies
description: Stand start under the bulge and pull up onto the slab.  Move up the slab till you connect with unknown solider. Good slab warmup

name: Foreplay
description: to the left of the dozer wall. starts on good side pulls go up and left. the low angle slab is a dab factor but a life saver

name: General Porcupine
description: Updated: Was told this rock has been climbed before. It was covered in moss in Spring 2015, so we cleaned it and climbed this line. Leaving it here for posterity. Will change name, grade, FA if asked to.    Played around on this boulder and came up with Private Porcupine line (been done before?). Was there with Paul who spotted more holds and we worked to connect them. General Porcupine is the result.    Sit start low left on a thumb down crimp and sloper gaston. Move right and up and right again along seam. Crux is leaving the seam for crimp holds out right before the finishing jug moves. Good fun.    Proposing V3-4. Heel hook was key for me, interested in seeing alternate beta.

name: IPOD Army
description: Start on the right side of the boulder using the rail and heel hooking meet up with my stereo and top out.  I am sure this has been done as it was pretty clean but I could not find it on here.  Anyone with info on the FA/name please let me know and I will change name.

name: Jaws
description: The crux is getting your ass off the ground and making a right handed lunge to a good hold, all while using terrible feet. Continue to follow the sharp crack out right until you top out at the peak of the boulder.

name: Jaws Stand
description: Good warm up for the harder lines in the area.

name: Jim's Exit
description: Start on Andy's Problem then move up and left finish is slightly easier.     again, not sure how it goes tried both a few years ago. If someone could give me some more info that would be great.

name: The Juggernaut
description: Stand starts on a left hand crimp and a right hand undercling. This problem is definitely more challenging the shorter you are.

name: Luke's Jaws
description: campus start on crimp rail on far right side of the "jaws" boulder. Do 2 moves on slopers and et the good seem. follow seem into "lukewarm persistence".

name: Lukewarm Persistance
description: One of the top V7's for the area. Same crux start as 'Jaws', then from the jug cut out left up the corner to finish. Hold broke awhile back, the finish is now better but not harder.

name: Lushes Lip Traverse
description: "Sit start on lowest rail and make one move to lip and traverse left around the corner to finish."

name: My Stereo
description: Nice line that goes right up the middle of this boulder. Start on the rail and setup for an awkward but cool dyno to a slopey jug. Then crank out a big lock-off to top out.

name: Nic-o-rete
description: A decent warm-up that could clean-up with more traffic.  Start with hands matched on the arete and feet matched on large flat foothold that forms the base of the boulder.  Move up to the break, then back right (high dab factor here), finally moving back up left and to the top.  Be careful on the top out.  To descend, walk towards the Juggernaut boulder.

name: No Mas
description: A sharp little bugger. This problem originally had a great deal of moss covering the top out; the problem also has very SHARP holds.  No more moss; no more attempts because the holds are too painful. No Mas, get it?      Begin standing with matched hands, move up seems (SHARP) to the top.  Be careful not to fall onto the slab.

name: onion left slab
description: Slab on to the left of the onion.  Stand start matched on a positive crimp and poor feet.  Move up and use the left arete.  Careful of the tree directly behind you.  not sure if this had been done before but I am assuming so.  Please update info if you know it and I will change FA/name.

name: The Onion
description: Sit start in a stretched out position with a right heel hook. Then with your left hand staying on a sloper, bump your right hand up numerous bad crimps. And either dyno or static the top.

name: Origins of Symmetry
description: Start in shield on RIght arete of the "absolution boulder. Pull hard on small hold with bad feet and achieve seem then traverse around corner into absolution then up.    you could go direct, but I was scared.

name: Payback
description: A very Squamish-esque line. This climb took me forever until I came here when it was about 40 degrees and it went right away. Being that its a sloper fest it is a very temperature dependent problem. Depending on the weather it could go anywhere from V5 to V9. Start with hands matched on the v-shaped edge. Follow the slopers to a seam then top out over the nose/peak of the boulder.

name: Pit Fall
description: Same start as councelor. climb right to the arete and then go up   you will be climbing over a pit, do not fall.

name: Poppy Cock
description: Even though this problem is right next to 'Vag Badger', it is a completely different style. It is a sit start followed by slopeiness.

name: Private Porcupine
description: See General Porcupine. Direct finish, straight up from start holds.    (Likely climbed circa 2005 by Jim Merli and company. No clear recollection of the line or name. Will update name, grade, FA as requested.)

name: The Prow
description: SDS between two boulders.  Climb up the vertical face for 4 feet untill it turns into a 45degree overhang.  Using the face and the left arete top out.  Sticking the lip is the crux.

name: Puffer Cheeks
description: Start to the left of the hole between the boulder and the ground. Use 2 good holds a few feet apart, about a foot above the bottom edge of the boulder out to stand start.  Get feet up & go left and up.  Slab top out.  Nice warm up in the central area!

name: Purple Rain
description: sit start using jug right hand side pull and "ok" left hand pinch. from there move up into the dihedral and back onto the face topping out up and left from start. NEEDS MORE CLEANING! but could be considered on of the best?

name: The Seamstress
description: Goes up a arete with small sharp holds. Bad landing.

name: The Smoking Man SDS
description: Start seated and climb the lower half of Sticky Icky.  Then, instead of the traditional mantel to slab top-out, you cross left and climb the leftward arete.

name: The Smoking Man Stand Start
description: Start from the right hand pinch and good left hand ledge of Sticky Icky, before the top out.  Heel hook lip and climb the leftward arete of Jim's Boulder.

name: Sticky Icky
description: A very steep arete that is trickier than it seems. Work the crux crimps down low and then head for the classic top out. Very popular.

name: Time is Running Out
description: Work your way up the arete with some highsteping to help you gain the committing move off the undercling. Perfect crimp rail to start, scary mantle to finish.

name: Tombstone
description: Cool looking tower, if only it had a better line on it. Find the obvious spire of rock in the middle of the main cluster leaning towards the north. Starts on the left side hugging the two corners. Climb up to a jug then pull over onto the slab for the finish.

name: Tugboat
description: A unique boulder for Sawmill, Tugboat features compression climbing on a suspended boulder. Begin with left hand on the good side-pull just above head height and right hand on the triangular pinch that is located on the underbelly of the boulder. Compressing the arête feature, climb up and top out via a difficult mantle.

name: Umberger Helper
description: I thought this short and simple problem was very good. Stand start, then do a couple of crimp lock-offs.

name: Unknown Soilder
description: SDS on crimps, move to a large jug, then up to a cool gaston.  Pull around onto the corner onto the slab and top out using crimps.

name: Vag Badger
description: Are we at Taylors? The rock in the beginning of this problem is very basalt like. Crimpy deadpointing start.

name: Veyron Arete: (Was The Turnstile Project)
description: This is a project Jim Merli has been looking at for years.  No one has yet done it.  As far as we know....    Nic Oklobjzia has made the first send of this long-looked at line on Oct. 30th, 2010.  He claims a difficulty rating around v10.  Go forth and repeat!

name: Warm Up Slab Shorty
description: Climb the short arete using large jugs.  Short but fun.

name: Warm-Up Slab
description: A very fun slab. Somewhat tall, and has this line of slopey pockets that you follow. A great topping out view too.

name: The Woodchipper
description: Start on lowest triangle hold move out the triangle's to you achieve the arete, continue up the arete to a challenging and heady top out.

name: The Woodpecker
description: Start right hand pinch edge, left hand undercling. Establish on boulder and make big move to large edge, continue up   Small holds and pods to the Scary finish. A full value boulder problem.

name: Dirty Girl
description: A fun but slightly tricky slab. Stand start on left side of the dihedral with left hand on a good side pull and right hand on the arete about shoulder height. Establish feet and climb straight up. Right wall seems detached and is off for the grade. Probably VB or V0 if using the right wall.

name: One Star Motel
description: Sit Start with hands on small ledge in the center of the aete. Climb straight up the arete.

name: PROJECT
description: Starting in large pocket on the left side of the face (right of the dihedral) Climb up face without traversing into the crack system or using the detached wall to the left. Is it an eliminate? Maybe. But it climbs directly and seems worthwhile to me. Also might be the only harder line in the Reach Around area. At least V8. Could be a lot harder.

name: Arrowhead
description: This route climbs the small detached triangular block located just North of the Underbelly Boulder. Sit start on the right side, and work your way up the two aretes.

name: False Hopes
description: This climb follows the obvious line created by the sinuous finger crack. Sit start on the left side of the boulder. Using the horn, make a powerful move into the crack and traverse right and then up the low angle rock.

name: Inny or Outy
description: With your feet on the ground, stand start in the thin finger crack. Traverse the crack until you can establish your feet in it. At this point tend leftward, and climb the center of the belly. This route eliminates the first hard move of Sandbagadocious, making it a great way to experience the exciting moves on the belly.

name: Old Boy (I'm too old for this s *t)
description: Sit or squat start with hands on large side pull on the right side of the seam/crack. Move up and to the right following the arete until you reach a large "dish" hold about two thirds the way up the right side of the boulder.

name: Old Boy Stand
description: Stand or Jump start to large right hand jug and large left hand side pull. Traverse up the arête to the right until you get to a "dish" jug about two thirds up the right face of the arête for an exciting top out.     This is the 2nd half of the boulder problem "Old Boy"

name: Sandbagadocious
description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder. Using the horn, make a powerful move into the crack until you can establish your feet in it. At this point tend leftward, and climb the center of the belly.

name: Beauty of Dreams
description: climb the arete, once you get started the holds show up. Need another 100 feet of this.

name: Don't worry so much
description: The slightly overhanging chimney is a classic short climb. Good stemming helps. Getting up onto the last block is the crux.

name: Learn from Mistakes
description: Slab climb that works your balance. Fun

name: Light a Candle
description: Small overhanging finger crack helps but you must get your feet up high and smear for your life as you search for the next hold.  Squeeze into the dihedral there's holds somewhere, stack your feet and push up to the finish.

name: New Thoughts
description: short climb with positive hand holds on the traverse to anchors. Kids love this route

name: No 1 can make u
description: Slab with some finger cracks It's all about footwork. Great top out boulder route. Also great for dry tooling.

name: Elyse's Revenge
description: A short sport route climbing a slopey and scrappy arete.  The rock quality is poor but large pieces are not likely to come off...work your way up and pay attention to your feet.   One of the top anchors is a spinner...

name: Encouraged By Coffee
description: Short but Sweet. Bouldery off the ground to a jug. If your shorter it could possibly be the hardest single move on the route. Traverse the horizontal crack to your first piece (#4) about 10ft up. If your not comfortable climbing to that point a few pads would help. The Crux is about 3/4 of the way up and a little spicy getting to your last piece.   You can climb the route (name Unknown) To the left to get up top and build a gear anchor. You’ve got to get a bit creative. Look for the old bolt stubs up top. These can be slung with a stopper and incorporate into your anchor.    Worth the time? For how short it is, it has great movement and is a little exciting up high. If this route seems too short for ya then pile up the pads! Boom just like that.. 30ft doesn’t seem so short anymore! This would make for a great highball Boulder! Have fun!

name: Uncharted Waters
description: 7 bolts lead to rings at the anchor. A single ring gets you out of the gully back down to the bike path. Lots of loose rock.

name: contivance
description: crappy bouldering located at the stillwater Boomsite (not at the ice climbing area, its across the river)(in MN). The best and one of the only bouldering problems in stillwater, very cool technical V3 , top out on a big jug about 8 feet off the gound

name: Arcarsenal
description: Powerful reachy moves lead to a fantastic finish on the arete.    Broccoli Command in the video.

name: Choppin' Broccoli
description: Powerful reachy moves gain an easy slab finish.

name: Crack Kills
description: Venture into the omnious cave to the West of the Dead Leaves Boulder and you may find a dead animal, because Crack Kills. The ceiling of the cave has an perfect hand crack. Follow this crack out and over the bulge!

name: Dead Leaves and the Dirty Ground
description: Start on lowest undercling sitting on the ground. Make a big move up and right to triangle shaped jug. From the triangle make a huge move to the amazing slope and top out, up and right.     One of the Best V7's in the midwest.

name: Easy Peasy
description: This is the easy slab to the right of the Craft Arete.

name: Relationship of Command
description: This is the perfect arete problem. The feet tend to be good; however, the poor crimps and sloping arete demand balance, precision, and core strength. Sit start low and work your way up the left trending arete!

name: Tetanus Kettle (Minndala)
description: Start High in small crimps (may be a stacked pad start). Pull on and with terrible feet make a static move to a cool 2+ finger pinch. After gaining the pinch continue to the top of boulder.

name: Just the Fat
description: Climb the right arete of the Bacon Boulder.

name: Slab of Bacon
description: Stay true to the face. Climb up the center of the steep slab using small crystals. Then reach for good crimps two thirds of the way up the face.

name: The Claw
description: "Start on main face with left on top of the rounded fracture. Throw right and head up. Exit through the chimney for the V3 finish." Minnesota River Valley Bouldering

name: Fists of Fury
description: This line is characterized by a thin seam that traverse where two large roofs meet. The initial sequence is fun and fluid. Sit start low on the right angling crack, and traverse the seam right. Then summon the strength of Bruce Lee to transition to the arete.

name: None Chuck
description: This line requires that you climb this slightly overhanging mass composed of numerous blocks. Sit start on the top of the hill. Make a powerful move off the ground and then its fun positive holds all the way to the top.

name: Soiled Bottom
description: A classic low angel slab. Edge your way up the blank face on small crystal edges. Half way up the face there is a horizontal crack that provides a momentary break before you have to resume edging up, and up, and up!

name: Wet Bottom
description: This is a tall and technical slab climb. The route is divided in the middle by a horizontal crack that is great for both your hands and your feet. The crux leaving this position of comfort and edging you way up to the lip.

name: Iron Cross
description: Climb the burly wide arete. Stand start with your hand on the arete and work your way up slopers and edges.

name: Jimmy Cracked Korn
description: Sit start on the obvious right angling crack, and enjoy easy fluid movement. Ignore the ferns and fly right to the top.

name: The One
description: Sit start on the left side of the face just under the overhang. Move into the amazing undercling and work up the face avoiding the big crack to the right.

name: Romeo Must Die
description: Sit start under roof on obvious start jug ledge. Make moves to lip and traverse right. Climb up the arete to finish on Iron Cross.

name: Juniper Judo
description: Climb the obvious face. start standing by bear-hugging the proud arete and vertical crack. Make moves directly up, staying on the face, and top out on the big ledge.

name: Bellerophon
description: Short but both technical and powerful. Sit start at the lower right side of the overhang. Establish your right hand as low as possible on the sloping arete, and your left on the lowest crimp. Climb up and left to slay this monster, and earn the title of Bellerophon.

name: Chimera
description: Stand start with your hands on the two large pinches in the very center of the slab. Climb the slab using interesting features. At the top there is an enormous rail. I guess Chimera is not that nasty after all.

name: Impossible Arete
description: Sit start low on the awesome blocky pinch. Make the first move and achieve the impossible.

name: Iwannahuck
description: Sit start on crimpy flake. Throw for top.

name: Mission Impossible
description: The namesake for the boulder itself, and with good reason. This is a classic. Sit start really low, under the overhang. Use the large blocky undercling with a perfect square thumb catch and establish yourself using the arete. Climb up using poor crimps and slopers.

name: Take the Mission
description: Sit start on the lowest corner you can find. Yep, way over there. Where are you climbing? ...well just follow the lip leftward. Traverse the lip all the way around the boulder. When you get to the top enjoy a little Tom Cruise moment.

name: Feelin' Lucky
description: Traverse the lower crack on the face of the Wee Munter Wall. Stand start on the large block on the right side of the wall and traverse the lower crack to the right. If you are feeling bold continue up for an easy finish.

name: Homestar Runner
description: Sit start at Slopish holds, up right to notch.

name: Nada Nun Chunks
description: Sit start to the right of the dihedral, on the large hold and throw left and then head up the dihedral.

name: Ranger Direct
description: Sit start on the right side of the wall using the large oval shaped hueco. Climb directly up the face. Make a large move to gain the lip directly above the hueco, rather than climbing up to the left and topping out through the "V' notch.

name: Texas Ranger
description: Sit start at eye shaped hole. Up left to Notch.

name: Too Short
description: Climb the overhanging arete! Sit start low with your left hand on the slopping undercling and your right hand on the poor crimp pinch. Work your way up the arete. If you find yourself using the large crack to the right than you should rethink your beta.

name: Easy Slab
description: Climb a number of very easy, low angle, slab problems on the southern side of this boulder.

name: Pocket Change
description: Stand start, left hand on the arete and right on crimps.

name: Project
description: Climb the right arete. This is not V-easy, the grade is simply a place holder.

name: Layback Finger Crack
description: This route is short but technical. Layback the finger crack working your feet up until you can reach positive holds over the lip. Then mantle your way over the top.

name: Monky's Wedding
description: Start with your hands on the enormous horizontal granite flake. Then make a burly deadpoint for a shallow dish on the lip. Work your feet up and top out with whatever you've got.

name: Sun Showers
description: This is a beautiful overhanging granite face. Stand start on a good crimp. Work your way up on progressively worse crimps until your reach the lip, a spectacular jug rail.

name: Sun Showers Sit
description: This is a beautiful overhanging granite face. Sit start on a good crimp. Work your way up on progressively worse crimps until your reach the lip, a spectacular jug rail.

name: Ewe Aint Kiddin'
description: Climb the right arete.

name: Mutton On the Edge
description: Start on the left arete and finish up the crack to the right.

name: Oh Sheep
description: Climb the center of the face,

name: Jack Mormon
description: Same start as the Swedish Lightning. From the jug move through the crack to the right.

name: Karo Syrup and Bulldozers
description: Sit start on the far right of the North face, and move left traversing the crack. Note: The block that forms this crack is hollow. Climb consciously.

name: Swedish Lightning
description: On the right side of the face there is arguably the largest hold at Swedes. Grab this and move left through interesting crimps. Head straight up, and finish in the center of the East face.

name: Swedish Lightning Left
description: One the right side of the face there is arguably the largest hold at Swedes. Grab this and move left through interesting crimps. Continue left and up.

name: Swedish Meatballs
description: Near the Southeast corner, find the distinct crimp rail. Sit start matched on this feature, and move up through small crimps.

name: Swedish Slopers
description: Start low, on the Southeast corner of the boulder on the crimp rail. Work your way straight up through interesting slopers.

name: Project
description: More info to come

name: Do No Evil
description: Start left of the crack, move up onto the slab and continue rightwards.

name: Hear No Evil
description: Same start as See No Evil, the good hold in the center of the face, but move to the crack rather than moving left.

name: On the Edge
description: Start on the lower right of the crack and make a big move.

name: See No Evil
description: Work left to right on crimps.

name: Skinks Crack
description: The namesake for the boulder, and with good reason. This route traverses the unique crack that defines the Skink's Palace Boulder. Start on the farthest left side of the East face and work your way right, finishing up the North face. You will need endurance, jamming skills, and good eyes to spot the thin feet. Good luck.

name: Speak No Evil
description: Find the good hold in the center of the face. From here make a through, and then finish the problem.

name: Up the Lip
description: Start in the center of the east face near the left side of the crack. Make a through for a small dish just above the lip, and continue up and over.

name: West Face
description: The West face is both a great place to warm up, and to down climb from some of the more difficult routes. Just note that many of the perfect plates that make this face interesting are hollow and may break off.

name: Black Tomahawk
description: Sit start on the jug and head up and left on the rail. Head straight up at the vertical seam.

name: Tric Troc
description: Sit start with left hand on the jug and right hand on on a sloper. Head up and get creative.
From ledge on 16 step right and straight up the over hang. Stick the sloper and top out. Crux is finding the sloper and pulling up.
Goes left of the A-shaped overhang. Pull through and finish by moving left.    #24 (5.12b) starts up the right side of the overhang and traverses to meet #23.

This small left-facing corner has a finger crack that runs to the top. The crux is right off the ground where an awkward bulge without any solid feet just to the left of the crack makes for an interesting challenge.
Climb a flake to a shallow dihedral. A fun, somewhat bouldery start (for a 5.8) is the crux of the route.

name: Cracked Pipes
description: Start on the flake that looks like an arrowhead and move right into a couple of crimps that lead to the horizontal crack on the main face. A few slots in the crack lead to the microwave block. Make it here and push it to the top through the crack.

name: Dunns of Fun
description: A deadpoint off of some crimps to a sloping block. Stick that and move into the crack and up.

name: Finagle a Foot Slab
description: Stand start on a couple of crimps. Move up and slightly to the right over the ramp. Finagle some feet and reach for the lip.

name: Gateway
description: A sit start to "Cracked Pipes" adding one v-point. After the V5 start move, it is a test of power endurance to complete this boulder problem.  A pad at the start is helpful and kosher/legit to get to the starting holds. Watch for loose rock in the seam near the top of the boulder.

name: Jacob's Ladder
description: Start on the flake that looks like an arrow and move up into the series of flakes onto a slab taking you to the top. Slightly overhanging fun and easy beginner climb. Some of the flakes feel thin so be cautious. I did pull on them to no avail though. The rock is pretty strong. Spotters and extra pad on the rock to the left of this climb is ideal.

name: Phat Lip
description: Sit start with left hand pinching the arete/flake and right hand crimping just below. You can smear your left foot on the rock behind the flake as it is connected and part the same boulder. Pop up to perfect slopers and traverse the lip all way to the jug flake from Jacob's Ladder.

name: Wolf Attack
description: Starting on a crimp and somewhat good edge, work your way up the bulges. Get a foot up and mantle to the top. A fun albeit burly problem.

name: A Feathery Tong
description: 8/9/07: I'm surprised this route was not in already.  It has been about 5 years since I climbed it so I will try to edit this post if someone reminds me of details. It was fantastic.
